    <story id="133811544">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/02/16/133811544/Restrepo-A-Soldiers-Eye-View-From-Afghanistan?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133811544&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/gM72H8</link>
      <title><![CDATA['Restrepo': A Soldier's-Eye View From Afghanistan]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133811544&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133811538" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>1023</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133811538-353099.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1137&amp;aggIds=124208272&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133811538&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1137&amp;aggIds=124208272&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133811538&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1137&amp;aggIds=124208272&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Restrepo chronicles a year with a single platoon stationed at the Restrepo outpost in Afghanistan's Korengal Valley, considered one of the military's most dangerous postings.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Co-directors Sebastian Junger and Tim Hetherington spent 10 months with the platoon, capturing the daily lives of soldiers as they pushed back Taliban fighters and foreign insurgents.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[The filmmakers consciously avoided revisiting the political debates over the Afghan war, Junger tells NPR's Neal Conan. The soldiers "really don't talk about their politics. But their reality, their emotional reality, is not often reported on. ... We really wanted to somehow give the nation access to that reality."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[Junger and Hetherington also hope their film will help viewers think more critically about the needs of soldiers as they return to civilian life. "Many of these young men were going through some of the most traumatic experiences in their life ... living daily with the risk of death, or watching friends die around them," says Hetherington.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA["Ultimately, these young men that we've instrumentalized and sent out there ... on taxpayer dollar are coming back home," Hetherington says. "And we have to make a space for them, we have to ... realize what they've been through."  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133750467">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/02/14/133750467/Domestic-Violence-Is-Never-Funny?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133750467&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/fiizLw</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Love Doesn't Have To Hurt]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133750467&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133750446" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>258</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133750446-766627.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1057&amp;aggIds=10617064,4497726&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133750446&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1057&amp;aggIds=10617064,4497726&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133750446&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1057&amp;aggIds=10617064,4497726&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[It is Valentine's Day, a day when we celebrate love. And even with all that is going on in the world, I think it's important to take a moment to think about our intimate relationships and what we want them to be.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[So, take a minute, if you will, to imagine that you are at a restaurant and you see a man and a woman and she orders, say, french fries instead of a fruit plate … and the man kicks her under the table — so loud, you can hear it.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Do you think that's funny?]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[Or, let's say you are at a couple's house and the woman of the house tries to tuck into a bit of lemon meringue pie or a burger … and her partner shoves her face into the pie, or takes the burger and shoves a bar of soap into her mouth.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[Do you laugh? Or, do you restrain him and call the police?]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[I hope you call the police or, at the very least, that couple's minister, because what you just saw is called domestic violence.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[And it isn't funny.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[So why is it funny when it's a woman battering a man and regulating his food? And, for the coup de grace, hurling a soda can at him because some random woman smiles at him as she sits down next to them on a park bench?]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[You know what I'm talking about, right? What I just described is the scenario for that Pepsi Max commercial that aired during the Super Bowl.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[Now, many of the media writers and bloggers whom I follow seem to find it hilarious, but maybe that's because they've never been to a battered women's shelter, which is filled with women who have actually had men (who supposedly love them) shove their faces into food and hit and kick them over nonsense, like what they wanted to eat.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[And here is a news flash: The fact that the commercial shows a woman kicking and abusing a man does not make it OK.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[And don't get me started on the race factor — the couple in the ad is African-American and dark skinned, at that, and the unfortunate bystander who gets beaned with the Pepsi can, a petite blond woman. Here we go again — that tired stereotype — the castrating black woman; the weak black man; the ultimate object of desire and envy, the petite blond.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Excuse me while I throw up.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[I know there are people who want to tell me it's just a commercial and why are you bringing race into it, and blah blah blah.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[But can I just tell you? I am not the one who brought race into it. I can tell you, because I have filmed commercials, that nothing about a commercial is random. Every single aspect — the hair, the clothes, the mix of people, is considered and debated and chewed over. So whoever dreamed up that commercial — and the Pepsico press release tells us it was a 28-year-old man from Kansas City named Brad Bosley — decided that a black woman needed to be the one to issue a beat down to her man to keep him under control.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[Now let's compare this with the other Pepsi Max commercial shown during the Super Bowl, which featured a white couple. The woman is dreamily looking at her date, wondering if he wants kids and is nice to his mom. And the man is gazing at her wondering when he can get into her pants. But there's no physical violence.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[And, mind you, Pepsico is the same company that brought us, during last year's Super Bowl, a commercial that featured a little black boy slapping the face of a grown man who was checking out his mom's butt.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[I know, I know, TV shouldn't be that important. TV isn't a baby sitter, let alone a parent. But this is the Super Bowl, for heaven's sake — the most-watched TV event of the year. Moreover, commercials are aspirational; they are telling us not just who we are but what we should aspire to. And kids, as we know, watch everything we do. And many kids — and not just black kids — are being raised in homes with no consistent image of what a healthy, intimate relationship looks like. So they're looking everywhere for clues about what relationships are and should be.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[This is what we're telling them?]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA[I guess I just have to conclude that this is what Pepsi thinks of black people — they (we) are people who just can't keep their hands to themselves. So please don't be shocked if I just manage to keep my hands to myself when I pass that aisle in the grocery store.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA[That commercial, by the way, is called Love Hurts. Can I just tell you one more time ... no, it doesn't.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA[And Happy Valentine's Day.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133658112">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/02/10/133658112/in-tunisia-some-say-lives-have-changed-radically?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133658112&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/f3QzhA</link>
      <title><![CDATA[In Tunisia, Some Say Lives Have Changed Radically]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133658112&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133660770" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>242</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133660770-8673d3.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1126&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133660770&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1126&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133660770&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1126&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Tunisia was the first Arab country to throw off its autocratic ruler, inspiring protests in Egypt. While it may take months — and even years — for Tunisia to build a functioning democracy, many Tunisians felt the effects of freedom immediately.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[In just the past month, the lives of some have changed radically.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Tunisian entrepreneur Amel Jertila, for example, says things began to change as soon as the plane of leader Zine El Abidine Ben Ali lifted off from Tunisian soil, taking him into exile in Saudi Arabia.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA["We start to speak and criticize him, and I had a feeling of freedom that day, like something just, you know, it's a fantastic feeling," Jertila says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[On a recent day, Jertila sits in her small office with a big smile on her face. There's an empty space with a picture hook on the wall above her computer. That's where the obligatory portrait of former President Ben Ali used to hang.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"/>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA["We wanted to break that picture, and then we said no, we will not break it," Jertila says. "We're gonna go all outside, we're gonna burn it and give a message to the new government. We don't want to have any president picture in the future."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"/>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Jertila says the corruption and fear of Ben Ali's dictatorship was interwoven with a stifling bureaucracy. It was a sort of vicious circle, she says, that no one could escape.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[If you made any profits at all, they were taken away in taxes and government fees, Jertila says. She managed three small companies. She says she had to bribe port authorities if she wanted her shipments to clear in a matter of days and not weeks. And she says the president and his family monopolized almost every business sector — and that those who competed with them were often driven into bankruptcy.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA["The port was their private company," she says. "The port is not a port. It's them who managed the port. It's them who managed the airport. You cannot describe it. It's bigger than your imagination. They are everywhere, in every single sector."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[Across town, criminal lawyer Najet Irgui, 33, also says she has felt the effects of the regime change. She says her profession is undergoing its own revolution because under Ben Ali there was no independent judiciary.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[ "Ben Ali's government told judges how they should decide cases and how they should work," Irgui says.  "Judges would get a phone call, and if they refused orders, there would be repercussions."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[Both of these women say that just one month ago they would have been deathly afraid to speak with the media for fear that the reporter might be a spy.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[People everywhere on the streets of Tunisia's capital say they are exhilarated to be able to speak freely for the first time. Outdoor cafes have come alive with conversations on topics other than football. But the biggest difference now, locals say, is the happy and hopeful expressions on people's faces.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"/>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[Jertila shows off her collection of ergonomic, recyclable office furniture. She says she wants to introduce Tunisian businesses to the "green" concept. This latest shipment of furniture arrived at the port in mid-January during the revolution.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[ "When the port was open again I wanted [to] clear it out," Jertila says about her shipment. "I knew that I had to pay to speed up the job. So I was thinking, I pay, I don't pay. People died for this. I shouldn't encourage them anymore; and then I said — I will not do it!"]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[Jertila told port authorities they had the legal documents to clear the shipment normally, and if it was held up they would have to explain why.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA["So I put them in front of their responsibility, and in this situation they were scared," Jertila says. "I got my container out after three days, which is a very, very good sign for me that things are changing."  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133619351">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/02/09/133619351/a-birth-defect-breakthrough-prenatal-spinal-surgery?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133619351&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/h7elbT</link>
      <title><![CDATA[A Birth-Defect Breakthrough: Prenatal Spinal Surgery]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133619351&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133629773" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>257</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133629773-ce6ca6.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1128&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133629773&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1128&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133629773&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1128&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[It's a landmark in the controversial, 30-year-old field of fetal surgery: Surgeons are reporting success in treating a common, serious birth defect called spina bifida — before birth.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Spina bifida is a hole in the spine that sometimes allows a loop of the naked spinal cord to protrude outside the body. Such neural-tube defects are down 30 percent because more expectant mothers are taking folic acid pills and dietary supplements. But about 1,500 babies are born with spina bifida every year, and many are destined to have severe lifelong disabilities.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[A new study, published online in the New England Journal of Medicine, shows that repairing the most severe form of spina bifida during pregnancy can reduce the paralysis and brain damage that often result when the defect isn't corrected until after birth.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[The surgery is delicate and risky for both mother and fetus. Doctors must make a three-inch incision in the mother's uterus to expose the fetus, which is typically about four inches long at this stage. They then put the exposed piece of spinal cord — between the size of a raisin and an almond — back where it belongs, and suture layers of tissue to keep it in place and prevent cerebrospinal fluid from leaking out.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[The study of 183 pregnancies shows that children who had the spinal operation in utero were twice as likely to walk unaided later. At age 3, 42 percent of those who had the prenatal operation were walking by themselves versus 21 percent of those who had the surgery after birth.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Brett Hallman is in the lucky group. When he was a 25-week fetus, he was the 55th patient who had fetal surgery for severe spina bifida at Children's Hospital of Philadelphia.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Brett's mother, Tara Hallman, says she and her husband Jake knew the operation was a success months later, when Brett smiled, sat up and crawled on schedule.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA["When he walked at 17 months without any braces — without anything — it just took my breath away," Brett's mom says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[A Landmark Study]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[But doctors who treat spina bifida say there's something even more important: Fetal surgery reduces a child's need for a lifelong shunt — a tube to carry cerebrospinal fluid from the brain to the abdomen. Without the shunt, fluid can build up, causing devastating brain damage or death.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[More than 80 percent of the children who had the surgery after birth needed shunts, compared to 40 percent among those operated on prenatally.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA["From a medical point of view — even though walking is quite nice — for the long-term overall outlook for these children, being free of a shunt is probably the single most important aspect," says Diana Farmer, a study coauthor and chief of pediatric surgery at the University of California at San Francisco.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Farmer says the new study is a landmark for the field.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA["This is the first time that fetal surgery has ever been attempted and validated for what we think of as a non-fatal birth defect," Farmer says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[Since surgeons at UCSF first did fetal surgery three decades ago, the field has been controversial. "People thought it was quite a heretical thing to do, and quite risky for women," farmer says. "Prior to this, we only considered fetal surgery in a circumstance where either the fetus would not survive pregnancy or the baby would be likely to die soon after birth."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[But she thinks the tide is beginning to turn — partly because other procedures, such as donation of part of a liver from a living relative, "have demonstrated that it is ethically reasonable in certain circumstances for someone to undergo a medical procedure for altruism, essentially — to help someone else."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA['Not A Cure']]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[But Scott Adzick of The Children's Hospital  of Philadelphia, lead author of the new study, stresses that fetal surgery for spina bifida "is not a cure. We think that we can help kids."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[There were some downsides: Nearly four out of five babies in the fetal surgery group were delivered prematurely, compared to 15 percent among those who got the operation after birth. So the fetal surgery group had more respiratory distress and other complications of prematurity. But there were no more deaths in one group versus the other.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA[One of the biggest risks is to the moms. Surgery weakens the uterus, which could cause a disastrous uterine rupture if the woman goes into labor, though this didn't happen during the study. The uterine incision also means that all subsequent babies will have to be born by caesarean section.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA[And as Tara Hallman testifies, even the most successful outcomes of fetal surgery aren't perfect. Although Brett is now an active 7-year-old who swims and plays other sports, he has to work to keep up physically.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA[And he has some bladder and bowel problems — but nothing, his mother says, that can't be managed. For instance, Brett can't urinate normally, so he's learned to insert a catheter every few hours.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="23"><![CDATA[Tara Hallman says he hasn't let his condition get him down. "Everybody has their challenges in life, and everybody has their battle scars, as we call them," she says. "This is his. And it's something that he's actually very proud of. He loves to show people his scar. It's actually part of his identity."  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133493823">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/02/07/133493823/chicago-code-this-time-the-good-cops-get-a-shot?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133493823&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/eMNbDM</link>
      <title><![CDATA['Chicago Code': This Time The Good Cops Get A Shot]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133493823&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133563858" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>386</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133563858-cbf483.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1138&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133563858&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1138&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133563858&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1138&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[If you watched the Super Bowl on Sunday, you saw plenty of promos for the new cop show from Shawn Ryan and the Fox network. It's called The Chicago Code, and it's kind of the flip side of Ryan's first cop drama, The Shield — and it may turn out to be just as compelling.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[In The Shield, Vic Mackey (Michael Chiklis) and company were corrupt cops who would even kill their fellow officers to protect their power base and their often ill-gotten gains. Yet over the years, we rooted for Vic Mackey rather than for the various police captains and lieutenants who tried to expose and fire him.  He was like Tony Soprano with a badge — it was easy to like the guy, so long as you didn't look too closely.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[The Chicago Code, premiering Monday at 9 p.m. ET, flips that equation.  In this show, the big corrupt figure is Alderman Ronin Gibbons, played by a smooth-looking Delroy Lindo (Get Shorty). He has the makings of a classic TV villain, and he plays each scene with an almost snake-like smugness — like a black Chicago version of J.R. Ewing. Gibbons is the Chicago power broker with his hand in everything — legal or illegal. He recently appointed the city's first female police superintendent, Teresa Colvin (Jennifer Beals), and he expects her to be subservient, naive and easily controlled.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[It's the same logic that got Jimmy Stewart appointed as a junior senator in Mr. Smith Goes to Washington — and Teresa's appointment backfires just as quickly. She, too, turns out to be incorruptible and annoyingly persistent, and decides to target Gibbons with a secret investigation. She enlists, as her major confidante, her former partner when she was a cop on the beat — Jarek Wysocki, played by another Showtime cable star, Jason Clarke from Brotherhood. He is reluctant to come aboard until she reveals her hole card: that she knows Alderman Gibbons is working with the Irish mob, because she has a cop working undercover in that organization.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[There's one other key character in The Chicago Code, at least in its first three episodes. That's Caleb Evers, Jarek's brand-new squad-car partner. He's young, he's smart, and he's played by Matt Lauria, who plays Luke Cafferty on Friday Night Lights.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[All three of these good-guy cops come from excellent TV shows and turn in very strong performances. Lauria is understated but confident, and lets you see the intelligence behind his character's silences. Beals is strong enough to stand firm while dismissing a veteran cop who is furious at her, yet playful enough at other times to flash a quick smile or a quicker insult. And Clarke, as the moral center of The Chicago Code, is instantly likable.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Well, not instantly. The entire pre-credits sequence of Monday night's pilot — that all-important first impression — is so over-the-top it plays like an expensive parody of a TV cop show, rather than a real one.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[But ignore that, let the dust settle and relax, because from that point on, The Chicago Code quickly finds its way. It borrows a little from The Wire, HBO's landmark series about entrenched, corrupted city institutions, and a little from EZ Streets, the vintage Paul Haggis cop series that gave equal weight to its good guys and its bad guys. But those are great places to start.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[And what Shawn Ryan is doing here that is quite original — and may be almost revolutionary — is that he is swimming against the current of 21st-century television. These days, almost all of the smart and best shows are on cable, and the best TV talent has defected from broadcast to cable TV. Ryan, who helped lead that revolution, is now reversing field.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[There aren't many intelligent shows left on broadcast TV, but there are a few: The Good Wife, 30 Rock and Modern Family. And maybe, just maybe — like a few honest cops in a corrupted system — their presence, and their efforts, can still make a difference.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[David Bianculli is founder and editor of TVWorthWatching.com. He teaches TV and film history at Rowan University in New Jersey.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133306045">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2011/01/28/133306045/nasa-ceremony-marks-25th-challenger-anniversary?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133306045&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/eVqQYz</link>
      <title><![CDATA[NASA Ceremony Marks 25th Challenger Anniversary]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133306045&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133311363" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>0</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133311363-b27177.m3u?orgId=1&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133311363&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133311363&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[The 25th anniversary of the Challenger disaster was marked by a ceremony at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida attended by hundreds. Among those speaking at the event was the widow of the shuttle's commander, as the AP reports:]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"/>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA["June Scobee Rodgers, the widow of Challenger's commander, Dick Scobee, urged the crowd to 'boldly look to the future' not only in space travel, but in space and science education. She was instrumental in establishing the Challenger Center for Space Science Education."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"/>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[Florida Today has posted an extensive photo gallery from today's ceremony.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Seven crew members died, including teacher Christa McAuliffe, when the Challenger exploded 73 seconds after its launch from the Kennedy Space Center on January 28, 1986.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Christa McAuliffe's backup that day was Barbara Morgan. She spoke with Michele Norris on All Things Considered today about one of the most shocking moments in recent American memory.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[Morgan, who eventually made it into space on a shuttle in 2007, tells Norris that when she looks back on that day she focuses on the smiles and enthusiasm radiating from the Challenger crew as they headed to the launch pad.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[When asked how she thinks we should honor their loss, Morgan says:]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA["I would hope that we honor them by keeping the future open ... and by making sure that we have a robust space program that keeps moving us all forward."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[The Challenger crew on the day it exploded were: Commander Dick Scobee; co-pilot Michael Smith; Ellison Onizuka, the first Asian-American in space; Judith Resnik; Ronald McNair, the second African-American in space; Christa McAuliffe; and Gregory Jarvis.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133210707">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/25/133210707/jonathan-safran-foers-eating-animals-finds-welcoming-audience-in-berlin?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133210707&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/gLRlRk</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Jonathan Safran Foer's 'Eating Animals' Finds Welcoming Audience In Berlin]]></title>
      <audio id="133212622" type="primary">
        <title>Listen to the Story</title>
        <duration>0</duration>
        <description>American author Jonathan Safran Foer recently stopped in Berlin to talk about this latest book "Eating Animals."</description>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133212622-2c9e35.m3u?orgId=1&amp;aggIds=104686340&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133212622&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;aggIds=104686340&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133212622&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;aggIds=104686340&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[American author Jonathan Safran Foer believes that being a human entails responsibilities that the other animals don't have. And, according to Foer, such responsibilities include what we choose to eat and why.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Eating Animals, Foer's part personal narrative, part investigative report on factory farming has become a big success in Germany; 180,000 copies of the German language edition have been sold.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[On his recent book tour, Foer stopped in Berlin, a city that has become a familiar place to him. After his acclaimed first novels Everything is Illuminated and Extremely Loud and Incredibly Close, Foer was a resident fellow at the American Academy in Wannsee.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA["I have to say I am so excited to come here because the book got a very special response here,  and a lot of people would have said that Germany is a particular tough place for a book like this," he says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[Foer initially thought Italy and Germany would be the toughest places to sell Eating Animals because meat is such a big part of their culture.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[But the author's presence in Berlin coincided with Germany's recent dioxin animal feed scandal which has added another level of public awareness and interest to his philosophy.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Foer says one of the most destructive things about factory farming is that making food cheap has made us think that eating is cheap.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA["It used to be that you would work a really long day, precisely that you could cook a really nice meal and eat it over a long period of time with your family. Where is it where families talk? Where stories are told, values transmitted?  It's at the kitchen table, and that's something that has been taken away from us," Foer says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[In his kitchen, only vegetarian meals are prepared. The 33 year-old admits that it took him 20 years to stop eating meat completely. Now he is raising his two children as vegetarians.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[But that's not necessarily what he expects from his readers. He's a realist and feels happy when people tell him Eating Animals persuaded them to eat less meat.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA["Very few people can imagine themselves being vegetarian, otherwise they would be. But almost everybody can imagine eating less meat. And they would probably find it's not a deprivation; it's something that makes them actually feel better. I don't mean in terms of health, I just mean it feels good to act on your beliefs. Everybody knows that."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[Writing the book on factory farming, he used industry and governmental sources, relying on the most broadly accepted statistics. He says that was very important to him. And no one has complained about the facts - not even the farmers themselves. Just one point was contested, Foer says, with a smile on his face.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA["There is only one fact in the whole book that's being questioned. In passing reference, I referred to Hitler as being a vegetarian. I must have gotten three dozen letters saying that's absolutely not true."  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133118406">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/26/133118406/ohios-gov-kasich-put-on-the-seat-belt?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133118406&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/fFNuXL</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Ohio's Gov. Kasich: 'Put On The Seat Belt']]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133118406&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133233029" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>278</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133233029-f2201b.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133233029&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133233029&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Ohio's new governor, Republican John Kasich, has just a couple of months to deal with the worst budget deficit the state has ever faced.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[For two years, federal stimulus dollars helped offset declining state revenues, but now that money has stopped , and Ohio will likely see deep cuts in government spending.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Even before he took office, Kasich signaled a blunt approach in dealing with the deficit and in public relations.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA["They think they're going to be able to carve out their little piece of pork. They think they're going to keep their snouts in that trough," Kasich said last month in a speech to the Ohio Farm Bureau, referring to the so-called "special interests." "If they do, you lose. We all lose, OK. I'm not gonna stand for it."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[Already a deadline looms: Ohio's fiscal year begins July 1. The law requires Kasich to submit a balanced budget and a proposed new spending plan by mid-March to account for a projected $8 billion shortfall.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Still, Kasich says this is what governing is all about, and in his inaugural address earlier this month, he seemed to relish the challenge.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA["Get ready for an exciting time," Kasich said. "Put on the seat belt, because we're going."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[Kasich spent nine terms in the U.S. House of Representatives, where he chaired the budget committee. After leaving Congress a decade ago, he went to work for the now-bankrupt investment firm Lehman Brothers. Kasich also once hosted a weekly show on the Fox News Channel.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[He got elected with just 49 percent of the vote, ousting Democratic incumbent Ted Strickland. Candidate Kasich tapped into long-term economic anxiety in Ohio, where the jobless rate is just below 10 percent and was in double digits for most of 2009 and 2010.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA['Everything' Is On The Chopping Block]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[Ohio State University's Paul Beck says you have to go back to the 1930s to find a budget crisis so serious in Ohio.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA["It's a real challenge," he says. "It would have been a challenge for any governor. I think it's a big challenge for Gov. Kasich in particular, because he's already said he isn't going to raise taxes."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[The state of the economy, coupled with the nearly 400,000 manufacturing jobs lost in the past decade, have hurt revenues and driven up demand for services in Ohio.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[Kasich says government can work better with less. As for what is on the chopping block, Kasich says the government will look at "everything."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA["We look at privatization, we look at killing things that don't work," he says. "There are just no options that are off the table, except tax increases, because we can't stomach them."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[Under scrutiny is aid to cities, funding for education, possibly privatizing the Ohio lottery or leasing out the Ohio Turnpike. That's just a partial list. Kasich also thinks that huge savings can be obtained through changes to Medicaid. And he promises to take on public employee unions and their pension and benefit plans.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA["And of course, the need to have civil service reform, which is bankrupting a lot of our cities through things like binding arbitration," he says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[Bruising Political Battles]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[The push back has already begun. About 300 people representing a coalition of groups, including unions, protested outside the state capitol recently. They argued that slashing programs puts the burden on working people.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA["To the victor go the spoils, and I understand that," says State Rep. Bob Hagan, a Democrat from the struggling blue-collar city of Youngstown.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA[Republicans control the Ohio House and Senate. Hagan says given the budget situation, it's wrong to continue to give big tax breaks to higher income residents when they've benefited so much from big tax cuts over the past decade. Hagan has a message for the governor.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA["I think he has to be reminded he only got 49 percent of the vote — that's not quite a mandate," Hagan says. "I really want him to understand that there are a lot of people that could really be hurt and devastated by this."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="23"><![CDATA[At a statehouse luncheon for Ohio lawmakers from both parties, Kasich asked for Democrats to work with him on the budget — but he also stated a political reality.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="24"><![CDATA["Let's just be honest. Many of you are not gonna go for this budget we're gonna do," he said. "OK, I got that. That's cool. Republicans are gonna probably carry most of the load. I hope I'm gonna be wrong."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="25"><![CDATA[Kasich did say to lawmakers that he'd never let political differences get personal.  But that doesn't mean Ohio isn't in for some bruising political battles — and they may begin right away.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133123382">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/23/133123382/super-stretched-songs-produce-cosmic-results?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133123382&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/dNDGOM</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Super-Stretched Songs Produce Cosmic Results]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133123382&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133162597" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>315</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133162597-1f7a09.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1039&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133162597&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1039&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133162597&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1039&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Back in August, a recording of Justin Bieber's "U Smile" went mega-viral on YouTube, earning over 1 million hits.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[But it wasn't the original song — it was a version slowed down by more than 800 times its original speed.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[The slow version sounds cosmic and ethereal. Last week, a similar recording went viral, this time a stretched version of the theme from the movie Jurassic Park. Listeners compared it to the early work of Brian Eno.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[As it turns out, almost any song slowed down to the extreme seems cosmic, from Train's "Hey, Soul Sister," to Eiffel 65's "Blue."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[Aaron Ximm, a sound artist from San Francisco, tells Weekends on All Things Considered host Guy Raz it's because slower music forces our brains to "downshift" to a slower listening plane. "You realize you don't have to be in a hurry — you can stay here for a while and take a look around with your ears," he says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Ximm hosted a listening event in San Francisco last year for one of the more popular examples of hyper-stretched music, Beethoven's Ninth Symphony. A Norwegian artist stretched it to last an entire day and called it, "9 Beet Stretch."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA["It was kind of mind-altering in a way," Ximm says. "At a certain point, I was aware of living in this slow or almost honey-like time."  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133146192">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/23/133146192/black-models-celebrated-as-runway-revolutionaries?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133146192&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/hp3eGq</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Black Models Celebrated As Runway Revolutionaries]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133146192&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133156196" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>314</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133156196-eff756.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1015&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133156196&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1015&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133156196&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1015&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[It was the fashion equivalent of a first-class prize fight — the Thrilla in Manila, only with high heels, not boxing gloves.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[In one corner, the titans of French haute couture: the houses of Yves St. Laurent, Christian Dior, Hubert de Givenchy, Emanuel Ungaro and Pierre Cardin — designers known for being elegant, traditional, proper.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[And in the other corner, some of America's best and brightest: Anne Klein, Oscar de la Renta, Bill Blass, Halston and a swiftly rising star, Stephen Burrows.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[The audience at the Palace of Versailles that November of 1973 was star-studded, too: plenty of American socialites, one of the richest women in France, and the former Grace Kelly, who became Princess Grace of Monaco.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[But as important as those ladies were, the event was transformed by the presence of several African-American models. According to Harold Koda, curator in charge of the Costume Institute at the Metropolitan Museum in New York, at the evening's end, fashion publicist Eleanor Lambert, who had dreamed up the event, described it this way: "It was as if, on this cold night, all the windows of Versailles had been blown open."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Around 200 people will gather Monday at the Costume Institute to celebrate these black models whose work that night made American fashion a contender on the world stage.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Koda says many people he interviewed who were at Versailles said the event nearly 40 years ago was special.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA["What made the presentation of the Americans so riveting, magical and overwhelmed the presentation of the French was the presence of African-American models," he says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Sandi Bass began her European modeling career the same year as the Versailles event and remembers how excited she was to hear about black models triumphing in the cradle of the French fashion establishment.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA["There was a certain kind of walk that we had at the time, and I'm just going to say it was pretty much the 'black girls' walk,' " she says. "We were free, we were spirited, we would smile. ... It was like a little trot down the runway."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[Bass, who worked for Givenchy for several years, says that after Versailles, a number of French designers turned to black girls as models and as inspiration.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[Many of the models served as both muse and sounding boards to the designers with whom they worked closely; the old don't-speak-unless-the-couturier-addresses-you protocol was swept aside, Bass says. "We had no holds barred, the personalities just flourished and opened, and this created an excitement for the designers as well as the audience," she says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Fashion historian Barbara Summers enjoyed a 17-year career with Ford, one of America's top modeling agencies. She says the models at Versailles caught the world's attention in part because of their numbers. There had been black models before, but they were considered exotic rarities.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA["At Versailles, they had never seen so many flagrantly beautiful black women at one time, so that was a revolution," she says — the turning-heads kind of revolution, not the chopping-heads kind.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[Summers says the Versailles audience was used to the chilly remoteness of the models who showcased European couture.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA["Black girls changed all that; they plugged fashion into what was happening now, and that meant R&B, rock 'n' roll, dancing, music, popular culture," she says.  "They brought the electricity of popular culture into fashion."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[Koda says Versailles came at the moment the world was changing: It was getting younger, there was a lot of social upheaval, and people were ready for change.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[Summers says the black models who presented at Versailles were pioneers in overturning an outmoded aesthetic.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA["They weren't planning on being revolutionaries, but they happened to be at the right place at the right time," she says. "And for a revolution to take place at Versailles, let me tell you, for these little black girls to be running around, kicking up a fuss, showing off, it had to be absolutely thrilling."  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133122149">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/22/133122149/giffords-begins-a-new-arduous-phase-of-recovery?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133122149&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/dWlKKu</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Giffords Begins A New, Arduous Phase Of Recovery]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133122149&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133136716" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>301</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133136716-584c25.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1128&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133136716&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1128&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133136716&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1128&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Rep. Gabrielle Giffords has begun the next phase of her recovery.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Nearly two weeks to the day after she was shot in Tucson, the Arizona congresswoman traveled Friday by ambulance, private jet and helicopter to Houston, where she will undergo lengthy rehabilitation at TIRR Memorial  Hermann Hospital, which specializes in the treatment of people with severe head injuries.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[As she left the University of Arizona Medical Center, where she was admitted near death on Jan. 8, people lined the streets and cheered.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA["There were several times we could hear applause in the ambulance," says Dr. Randall Friese, a surgeon who made the trip with Giffords, family members and other members of the medical team. "Gabby ... responded very well to that, smiling and, in fact, even tearing a little bit. It was very emotional, very special."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[At the other end of the journey, Houston neurosurgeon Dong Kim was impressed at how well Giffords is doing.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA["She looks spectacular — in all ways," Kim says. "She came into the ICU and she was alert, awake, calm; she looked comfortable. We were testing the vision; she didn't like us shining the light in her eye, wanted to keep them closed. And these are all very good signs."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Daily Progress]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[In the past week, Giffords has shown progress every day, say her doctors and her husband, astronaut Mark Kelly.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA["Every time I interact with her, there's something quite inspiring," Kelly said at a Thursday press conference at the Tucson medical center. "In two months, you'll see her walking through the front door of this building."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[By the end of this week, she was sitting up in a chair. Physical therapists got her to her feet and even outside in the sun. Doctors said she was able to pick out different stuffed animals and identify objects by color. And people marveled when she scrolled through photos on an iPad.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[When Giffords arrived in Houston, Dr. Gerard Francisco, who will lead the rehab team, couldn't have been more upbeat.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA["She has great rehabilitation potential," Francisco says. "She will keep us busy, and we will keep her busy as well."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Indeed they will, say experts in the rehabilitation of brain-injured patients. As optimistic as her doctors are, they say Giffords is just starting down a long and arduous road.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA["I tell patients when they arrive that they're going to work harder than probably they've ever worked in their lives," says Dr. Steve Williams, head of rehabilitation medicine at Boston  Medical Center, who is not involved in Giffords' case but has followed it closely. "They'll work to the point of exhaustion, but the payoff is very good in the end."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[Dealing With The Unknown]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[There's a lot that doctors don't know yet about the extent of Giffords' brain injury. For instance, they're not sure how much damage has been done to the areas that control her right arm and leg. Doctors say right now they appear severely weakened or paralyzed, so a lot of work will focus on that.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[But the biggest questions have to do with her cognitive, or thinking, ability.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[She's already demonstrated that much of her cognition is intact. She can follow simple commands, such as "raise your hand." To find out more, Williams says, the Houston team will need to put her through progressively more complicated tests.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA["To follow a command that has many processes, such as 'close your eyes, stick out your tongue and raise your hand,' she needs to remember the sequence of events," Williams says. "She needs to be able to perform all the events, and that's a complex task."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA[Specialists will also test her ability to think abstractly. That's not easy with someone who isn't yet able to talk. But Jeffrey Wertheimer of Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles says there are yes-or-no questions that can get at that.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA["I may say, 'Does the moon burn your skin?'" Wertheimer says. "I may throw something a little more complex, a little more ambiguous, a little more abstract."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA[Wertheimer, a neuropsychologist and expert in gunshot wounds to the brain, says different tests probe the ability of such patients to concentrate.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="23"><![CDATA["When you have left-hemisphere damage, going from the left eyebrow area back, one can expect some difficulties with attention and concentration," Wertheimer says. "We may be more vulnerable to distraction."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="24"><![CDATA['Waiting To See What Happens']]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="25"><![CDATA[Once Giffords can speak, assuming she does, Williams says, she'll be asked to do endless mental drills — basically, cognitive calisthenics.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="26"><![CDATA["The patient does the same task over and over and over so that they really learn and it maps into their memory," he says. "It's kind of like second grade, doing multiplication tables time and time and time again and singing songs so we could remember that two times two is four and two times three is six."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="27"><![CDATA[All this will take many months. Progress will go in fits and starts. There can be complications, such as seizures. It's not possible to know how far a given patient will get, or how fast.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="28"><![CDATA["One of the parts that is most difficult, I think, is waiting — waiting to see what happens," Williams says. "We look for the brain to be able to take over functions for areas that were injured. And that takes time."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="29"><![CDATA[Williams says the best strategy is to set achievable, short-term goals — and let those achievements add up over time.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133012168">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/18/133012168/giffords-recovery-brightens-news-out-of-tucson?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133012168&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/h7NJdr</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Giffords Could Be Released Within Days Or Weeks]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133012168&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133012335" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>237</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133012335-fa09d7.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;aggIds=132783213&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133012335&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;aggIds=132783213&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133012335&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;aggIds=132783213&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Doctors in Tucson, Ariz., are talking about the day Rep. Gabrielle Giffords will leave the hospital. One of the surgeons taking care of her says she may be just days to weeks from being transferred to a rehabilitation center.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[That bit of hopeful news was delivered at a hospital briefing Monday. It comes after a string of mostly positive news from her doctors since the shooting Jan. 8. But the positive news may not provide a completely accurate picture of what's going on.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Physicians taking care of Giffords have called her recovery to this point a miracle. A bullet traveled all the way through the left side of her brain -- from front to back, doctors say. Just days after the shooting, they reported she was able to follow simple commands. Then, during a visit from fellow members of Congress last week, she opened her eyes. Doctors were almost giddy.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[On Saturday, a breathing tube was removed from Giffords' mouth, and her husband Mark Kelly said she smiled.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA["Mark told me that he thought he may have seen a smile," said Dr. Randall Friese, associate medical director at the University Medical Center Trauma Center. "We're all very optimistic, so we could be wrong. But we all want the best, and sometimes we see what we want to see, but if he says she's smiling, I buy it."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[On Saturday, surgeons performed a tracheotomy on Giffords -- installing a new breathing tube in her throat and inserting a feeding tube. They also repaired damage to the top of her eye socket on the right side. Giffords was taken off a respirator, and her condition was upgraded from critical to serious.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA["I'm happy to say that within a few hours of the surgery, she was waking up," said Dr. Michael Lemole, a neurosurgeon at UMC. "Through the weekend, she came back to the same baseline she'd been before the surgery -- that same level of interaction she's been having with us. And that's all very good."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[Later a reporter asked a question that has come up at nearly every briefing: How much movement does Giffords have on the right and left sides of her body?]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA["I'm going to be real cagey with you here, like I have been in the past," Lemole said. "The family really doesn't want to go into that detail at this time."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[While a lot of information has been released, it's clear that some is being held back. Giffords is a member of Congress and a public figure, but she still has the right to medical privacy. That means every piece of news the doctors have delivered so far was approved by her family first.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA["No one is suggesting we're being fed false information," says Anita L. Allen, Henry R. Silverman professor of law and professor of philosophy at University of Pennsylvania Law School.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA["We're being fed information which is positive and hopeful, leaving open the possibility that she might well recover to a greater extent than some of our worst fears might suggest," Allen says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Allen contends that the public should be grateful for the bits of information that have been released because under current privacy laws, Giffords family could have said nothing. And frankly, she says, under similar circumstances, that's what a lot of us would want.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA["It's a little embarrassing, a little awkward, a little sensitive to have every aspect of one's self revealed to other people when one is in pain, when one doesn't look one's best, sound one's best." Allen says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[Maybe Giffords deserves a little private space, Allen suggests -- room to heal without all the gory details known to everyone.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[Perhaps with that in mind, her doctors say they're not planning any more briefings until there's a significant change in Giffords' status.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133023439">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/18/133023439/chinese-still-fans-of-obama-but-honeymoon-is-over?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133023439&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/fiSUdP</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Chinese Still Fans Of Obama, But Honeymoon Is Over]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133023439&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133029295" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>195</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133029295-c57d98.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1125&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133029295&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1125&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133029295&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1125&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[President Obama hosts visiting Chinese President Hu Jintao for a private dinner Tuesday night and then again Wednesday for a full state visit at the White House, including a 21-gun salute and an official dinner with dozens of guests.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Though there has been little noticeable personal chemistry between the two leaders in their meetings over the past two years, the Chinese people themselves were big fans of Obama when he was elected. Now, their feelings are more nuanced -- though still generally positive.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[When Obama visited China in November 2009, he held a town hall meeting in Shanghai that was the hottest ticket in town. Graduate student Qian Jin succeeded in getting into the event and got to shake the presidential hand.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA["He's like a rock star, and every student wants to shake hands. Highest moment for me and my friends, shaking hands with Barack Obama, probably is the highest moment," he says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[But Qian concedes, by and large, that on the policy front, Obama hasn't made much difference to either China-U.S. relations or the U.S. economy more generally. He says he thinks Obama was overhyped and that Americans are generally too emotional about their leaders.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA["In China, they are so pragmatic. They pay more attention to the real policy rather than the person. We say what people do is more important than what he is saying," Qian says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[And because oratory is not traditionally a part of Chinese political culture, nobody gets all worked up about beautifully crafted speeches, either. Tong Shijun of the Shanghai Academy of Social Sciences says that Obama as the first black president still resonates with many Chinese.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA["President Obama is a positive resource for public relations of the U.S. at the international level, because he sent the message that ordinary people can reach his or her ideals. In his words, 'nothing is impossible,' " Tong says, referring to Obama's "Yes We Can" motto.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[At Madame Tussaud's Wax Museum in Shanghai, young Chinese are lining up to take pictures of themselves with a startling likeness of the 44th president of the United States.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[Visiting 20-something Zhu Jieting says she thinks Obama is great and that people shouldn't be too impatient, because things take time.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[Pan Tao, 24, agrees. He says he still likes Obama, and that he prefers him to George W. Bush. Obama may be finding it difficult in this economic climate, Pan says, but at least he's not trying to solve things through war.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="133029178">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/18/133029178/Looted-Mansions-Become-Tunisian-Tourist-Spots?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=133029178&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/giuTEB</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Tunisians Loot Lavish Homes Of Former Ruling Clan]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=133029178&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133029161" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>241</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133029161-02b92c.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1004&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133029161&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1004&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133029161&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1004&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[In the days since the overthrow of Tunisia's dictator, looters have  ransacked a whitewashed villa in an upscale suburban neighborhood of  Tunis called La Marsa.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[The house belonged to businessman Moaz Trabelsi, one of the 10 brothers  of the ousted president's wife, Leila Trabelsi. And it's a scene that is  playing out across the country at homes owned by relatives of president, Zine El Abidine Ben Ali.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Tunisians say they want a complete break with their former ruler, They say the president, and in particular his wife and her family, abused power and enriched themselves at the expense of the country's people.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[On Tuesday, Tunisia's new interim government was on shaky ground. Four Cabinet ministers resigned and others threatened to do so in protest over the continued presence in the government of Ben Ali's allies.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[Portrait Of Excessive Decadence]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[After days of looting in that suburban villa, there's nothing more to take away. But still, hundreds of people still come every day to visit the wrecked shell.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[One of this day's visitors is Mounir Khelifa, an English professor at the University of Tunis. He points to a burned-out Porsche Cayenne and calls the mansion a "thief's" or "robber's" house.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[The swimming pool has a mattress floating in it. Broken furniture and women's magazines litter the yard. Families are walking through the villa's empty, trash-strewn rooms as if it were a real estate open house.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Khelifa says Tunisians despise the president they deposed, but they hate his wife even more. The 55-year-old former hairdresser is 74-year-old Ben Ali's second wife.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[Like the tentacles of an octopus, the Trabelsi clan wrapped itself around almost every sector of the country's economy, their critics say. They controlled the car dealerships, the banks, the airlines, the media and the major retailers.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[Amel Jertila, a 37-year-old who started her own company, says doing business in Tunisia was hell.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA["It was terrible. And you are scared all the time. What if I cross them one day in my life, what will happen to me? After years of work, we are scared of phantoms that are called Trabelsi and Ben Ali," she says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Cables from the U.S. ambassador in Tunisia that surfaced in WikiLeaks paint a picture of a family that lived in excessive decadence, while many Tunisians lived below the poverty level. Invited to dinner at the villa of Ben Ali's favorite son-in-law, the ambassador described ice cream imported from St. Tropez on a private jet and a pet tiger in a cage on the compound.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA['Giants With Clay Feet']]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[Just three days before the final wave of protests that brought Ben Ali down, writer Abdelaziz Belkhodja took the risk of distributing documents showing the extent of what he calls the mafioso activity of the president, his wife and her family.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA["It reached unimaginable proportions. These people wanted to take over the country. That's why they took the banks and the media. She appointed the ministers, because after his death, she wanted to keep control of the country," Belkhodja says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[He estimates that in their two decades in power, Ben Ali and his extended family stole about $20 billion -- twice Tunisia's national budget.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[Another magnificent villa -- this one on a hillside -- is the home of a simple primary school teacher whose name happens to be Adel Trabelsi.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[Inside the house, Tunisians are ripping out wiring and trying to detach some electric blinds from the windows. Everyone is smiling. Khelifa, the English professor, says no one in their wildest dreams would have imagined such a sudden and ignominious collapse of the Ben Ali-Trabelsi family.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA["We suspected that tyrannical power is weak. But to this extent, this kind of weakness is just amazing," Khelifa says. "I think if there is one lesson to be learned, it's precisely that dictatorships, they're giants with feet of clay."  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132493034">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/17/132493034/chk-plz-restaurants-try-texting-to-speed-service?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132493034&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/gONjY2</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Chk Plz: Restaurants Try Texting To Speed Service]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132493034&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="133002447" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>240</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1133002447-040619.m3u?orgId=329&amp;topicId=1049&amp;aggIds=97097438&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=133002447&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=329&amp;topicId=1049&amp;aggIds=97097438&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=133002447&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=329&amp;topicId=1049&amp;aggIds=97097438&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[The menu at Charlie's Kitchen, a dive bar in Cambridge, Mass., might not stand out for its cutting-edge cuisine. But the eatery is at the forefront when it comes to how customers can communicate with the wait staff.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[A sticker on the wall of a corner booth says it all: "Can't find your server, just text!"]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Charlie's is one of the first restaurants in the country to try TextMyFood, a new service that allows customers to communicate with their server via text messaging.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[Five minutes after typing, "I'm at table 3. I want a tossed salad with ranch dressing," a meal arrives at the table.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[Check, Please]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA["There are pros and cons," says Kristina Henry, a server at Charlie's. "It's great for a night like Friday night when we're really busy. It's packed and you're running around [and] people text like, 'Can I have my check please?'"]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Even though TextMyFood may make her job easier, Henry says she finds the service impersonal.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA["As a server, I would rather want to go to the guest and talk to them face to face and ask them what they would like instead of getting it through a computer," she says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Still, the technology doesn't replace the server.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA["It's not eliminating human contact," says Bob Nilsson, the president of TextMyFood. "There's always a server at the other end. You just want to have that contact sooner. If you can't see them and can't make that contact, rather than waving your arms or getting up, just use the natural communication and let them know what you need."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[Nilsson says the goal of the service is to increase the amount of money customers will spend. For example, guests are more likely to order another round of drinks if they text the request in the moment. If they can't find the server, they often pass.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[But not everyone at Charlie's Kitchen finds it useful to be able to text requests to their server.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA["I guess it seems kind of pointless because I can tell my waitress to her face what I want to drink," says customer Zach Brickett.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[Prank Texts]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[Another customer, John McSweeney, wonders if people will abuse the system.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA["It sort of occurred to me to maybe -- just as soon as we ordered our beers -- to take out my phone and be like, 'Beers/stat/now,'" he says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[Prank texting is indeed a problem.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA["I've gotten, 'Glasses are sexy.' I've gotten, 'Two of us need something and three of us need your number,'" says Joshua DeCosta, another server at Charlie's Kitchen.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[In response, some establishments -- where there's a lot of heavy drinking -- turn off the service after a certain hour. But other managers say they appreciate the ability to monitor guests.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA[If too many inappropriate texts come in from one person, it's time to cut them off.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA[Time To Tip]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA[It's not uncommon for restaurant or bar patrons to have to wait to pay even though they have their check in front of them and their credit card out. That's because servers aren't always in sight.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="23"><![CDATA[Now, instead of waving, a text will do.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="24"><![CDATA[A few seconds after typing, "T3. My credit card is waiting," into my phone, the server comes over to take my payment and smiles.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="25"><![CDATA[We've barely exchanged a word. I find texting extremely alluring. I message, she arrives.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="26"><![CDATA[Still, when it came to the tip, I left it the old-fashioned way -- on the table.  [Copyright 2011 WBUR]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132937255">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/16/132937255/for-gervais-another-trip-to-the-globes-sans-script?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132937255&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/enOUb9</link>
      <title><![CDATA[For Gervais, Another Trip To The Globes, Sans Script]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132937255&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132975233" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>628</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132975233-f98365.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1138&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132975233&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1138&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132975233&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1138&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Ricky Gervais can't believe his luck. Even after creating a few beloved award-winning TV shows, writing and directing films and cracking people up with his popular standup specials, the host of this weekend's 68th annual Golden Globe awards ceremony is still in awe of his own celebrity and the perks that come along with it. Gervais tells Weekend Edition Sunday host Liane Hansen that he is frankly amazed at the freedom he has had in his career.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA["It's not like a career. It's like I've won a competition," Gervais says. "I'm worried I'm dying, and the doctors got together with everyone in Hollywood and said, 'Just let him do what he wants ... just let him do anything. Let him be in all his favorite TV shows.' "]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Some of those favorite shows that have welcomed Gervais for guest appearances include Family Guy, The Simpsons and Curb Your Enthusiasm. He also recently filmed a conversation between himself and Jerry Seinfeld, Chris Rock and Louis C.K. -- whom he counts as his three favorite comedians in the world -- which will be edited down for an HBO special.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA["I'd be lying if I still didn't [have] a smile come across my face when I see my icon walk up to me and say hello, you know. It's crazy. It's strange. I had a normal job until I was about 36, 37. ... [Now] I'm walking down the corridor, and Al Pacino walks up to me, and goes, 'I just saw you in a terrific film about lying, terrific.' And I go, 'Yeah, you've been in a few good films as well yourself.' It's mad. It's crazy."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[Gervais hosted the Golden Globes for the first time in 2010. Back in 2004, Gervais won a Golden Globe himself for his performance in the British version of The Office, which was then airing on BBC America. Before that awards ceremony, Gervais spoke with Hansen about his aversion to celebrity and how thankful he was for his relative anonymity in the U.S.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA["The good thing is that no one knows who I am," he told NPR in 2004. "They probably think I'm a waiter. So I'm going to wear a red jacket, and then I think the people will leave me alone, definitely. I can't even go shopping for pants now without people looking in my basket."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Coming back to the Golden Globes seven years later as a third-time host and much more of a household name, Gervais says that he will stick to his off-the-cuff style of improvised remarks. He won't follow a script and has no qualms about drinking through the ceremony -- a technique that led to more than a few controversial remarks last year as he introduced celebrity presenters throughout the show.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA["I'm going all out," Gervais says. "They will never invite me back again. ... If they wanted someone to read an Autocue, there's lots of better people than me at that. And they look better. So whenever I'm hired, I'm hired for my particular cocktail of skills -- or lack of them."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[But more than his role as the master of ceremonies at the Golden Globes, Gervais wants people to recognize him for the things he himself has created -- like The Office or Extras. He knows that after the awards ceremony ends, he'll return to work on Monday morning with his writing partner Stephen Merchant and concentrate on creating his own body of work.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA["Winston Churchill said, 'If you find a job you really love, you'll never work again.' And that's what it feels like, you know. I went from the laziest, least ambitious man in the world to a workaholic, because I can't believe my luck. I cannot believe my luck," he says. "And some people listening to this are agreeing with me."  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132940408">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/14/132940408/giffords-staffers-the-office-is-open?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132940408&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/hghL6A</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Giffords' Staffers: 'The Office Is Open']]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132940408&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132940174" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>278</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132940174-a3da3d.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;aggIds=132783213&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132940174&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;aggIds=132783213&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132940174&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;aggIds=132783213&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Since last Saturday's shooting in Tucson, Ariz., Rep. Gabrielle Giffords' district office has become a mecca for mourners and well-wishers, and it has remained open despite her absence.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[On Friday, there was a welcome surprise as Pam Simon -- one of the staffers injured in the shooting -- returned to the office for the first time. Simon, who suffered gunshot wounds to her wrist and chest, walked into a sea of happy faces and open arms.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA["I happened to get hit by bullets, but all of you, especially those that were there, you got wounded too," she told her colleagues.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[Simon's arrival is the most visible sign that Giffords' staffers can perhaps begin their own healing. Since Monday, they have hosted a stream of constituents, friends and volunteers offering condolences and long hugs.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA["Well, this is a fraction of the type of stuff that has been happening here," says C.J. Karamargin, Giffords' communications director. "People have been coming by from all over the place."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Karamargin says staff members were still reeling from the initial shock of the shooting when they decided that opening the office on Monday morning as usual would send an important message. "No act of depravity would be enough to close down this small little outpost of our government," he says. "The office is open, our government is open, our democracy is open and that hasn't changed."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[So the basic work of a congressional district office goes on, helping Giffords' constituents with their problems, such as immigration, foreclosures and Medicaid denials.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[Sara Hummel Rajca handles immigration and veterans affairs for Giffords. She's also the staff photographer, so she was at the congresswoman's side when the alleged gunman started shooting. Rajca managed to find cover.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA["Not that I'm trying to repress anything, but working through this by keeping the office open is what Gabrielle Giffords and Gabe Zimmerman both would have done," she says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[The news that Giffords is recovering helps keep the staff strong, Rajca says. But the death of 30-year-old fellow staffer Zimmerman still seems unreal to her.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA["Tomorrow I want to walk in, go sit down at my desk and say hi to Gabe as he drinks his Dr Pepper as he comes in and chat about the weekend and, you know, have things be like they were last Friday," she says. "But it's not that way and time doesn't stop and we'll just keep going forward."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[Somewhere between the feelings of denial and acceptance, there are moments when the gravity of the week is inescapable.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Zimmerman was a social worker before he became a congressional staffer. Earlier this week, he was honored at the Capitol in Washington, D.C., when House Speaker John Boehner ordered the flags flown at half-mast.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[Karamargin's eyes well up as he talks about his friend.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA["When I turned on the TV and heard that, I broke down," he says. "He said 'Gabe Zimmerman died in the line of duty.' Soldiers die in the line of duty. Firemen die in the line of duty, police officers. First responders die in the line of duty. When do social workers die in the line of duty? It's just, this is tragic."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[As for his own mourning, Karamargin says he really hasn't had time for it yet.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[Back outside the office, there's a memorial of countless candles, flowers and dozens of placards with poems and prayers. Carmen Mayer, a semi-retired accountant, reads one that brings a smile to her worried face.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA["And love will hold us together, make us a shelter to weather the storm," she reads. "That's what's gonna happen. It's gonna take a while. A long time."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[Giffords' staffers will collect the placards and the many boxes stuffed with handwritten notes and letters of sorrow and grief. They plan to collate them in the hope that the congresswoman will, one day, be able to read them.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132834050">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/blogs/pictureshow/2011/01/14/132834050/weber?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132834050&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/eSV2Ci</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Portraits Of Haitians In Miami]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132834050&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132924380" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>260</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132924380-0f83a0.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1008&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132924380&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1008&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132924380&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1008&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Photographer Bruce Weber is best-known for his shots of models and celebrities. Think Vogue, Ralph Lauren and catalogues for Abercrombie and Fitch. In the early '80s, his photo of Olympic athlete Tom Hintnaus wearing Calvin Klein briefs -- featured on a Times Square billboard -- became iconic.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[But along the way in his 30-plus-year career, he has also used his photography to tell other, less commercial stories. In north Miami, he has mounted a solo exhibition at the Museum of Contemporary Art -- photos profiling the city's Haitian community.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[It's a community Weber knows well. He first visited Miami on a shoot for Calvin Klein and now it is his home. "I fell in love with the beach and the water," he says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[And while he came to Miami for the water, he said in an interview at his beachside home, he has been drawn to the streets of Miami's neighborhoods. "People always say to me, 'What's the best part of Miami?' And I say it's people."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[Weber tells the story of some of those people in his show, which includes 75 photographs taken over the last seven years in Miami's Haitian community. The show was inspired by a conversation he had with his friend, filmmaker Jonathan Demme after a screening of Demme's documentary about Haiti, The Agronomist. Weber asked Demme what he could do to help Haiti. "And he said, 'Bruce, take your camera, go to Krome, go to the people of Little Haiti.' "]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[That's Krome, as in the Krome Detention Center, a federal facility near Miami where Haitians are held pending deportation. In 2003, he went there with Haitian advocates and was shocked at what he found. Weber has visited prisons before on photo assignments, he says, "but never did I have a chill like I did when I went to Krome. And I saw men just treated so terribly -- just because of where they're from and who they are."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[In the exhibit, there's a portrait of a skinny young man, David Joseph, who was 18 years old when he arrived in the U.S and was detained by authorities. Attorney General John Ashcoft intervened personally in his case, writing an opinion denying Joseph bail bond while he sought asylum. He spent two years in detention before being deported back to Haiti.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[For his journey though the Haitian community, Weber had an expert guide. Marleine Bastien is well-known through her work with the non-profit group she heads, Haitian Women of Miami. She introduced Weber to the community and worked with him like a collaborator. She found that Weber is able to communicate with the Haitian community in ways that other people can't: "He becomes like their interpreter," she says. "He touches their soul and then he's interpreting to others what the Haitian people have been through."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Many of the photos are from 2003, focusing on forced detentions and U.S. immigration policies. But there's another, more recent set. After the Haitian earthquake, among the places Weber and Bastien visited was a hotel in Miami where medical evacuees were being housed.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[While there, Weber photographed four Haitian girls, all recovering from disfiguring injuries. They were hesitant to be photographed. But he convinced them, he says, by telling them they're as pretty as Beyonce -- whom he's also photographed. In the exhibit, his photo shows four young women smiling, beautiful, beaming with personality. That was especially so, Weber says with one of the girls, Barbara Adrien.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA["Her personality was so strong and so vibrant," he says, "that I can only compare it to the time I was photographing Leonardo DiCaprio when he was a young boy and we went to Coney Island together. And it was just like an explosion of life. You could have taken a million pictures of her."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[Weber's show will be at the Museum of Contemporary Art in North Miami through February. He says he isn't done telling the Haitian story, and is planning a trip soon to the island. "I'm hoping some day," he says, "that we have a better story to tell."  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132805670">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/12/132805670/teflon-governor-must-tackle-colo-s-budget-shortfall?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132805670&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/f1uPKY</link>
      <title><![CDATA['Teflon' Governor Must Tackle Colo.'s Budget Shortfall]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132805670&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132872321" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>273</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132872321-2d3401.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132872321&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132872321&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[In Colorado, Denver Mayor John Hickenlooper became  Gov. Hickenlooper on Tuesday.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[One of the first issues he faces is a budget shortfall  that could reach $1.5 billion, which is about 20 percent of the state's general  fund budget.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Hickenlooper came into politics after a successful run in the restaurant  business. And today, his public image is just about as amusing as his name. His  political ads get much of the credit for that.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[In 2005, he sky-dived in support  of a tax reform measure. And this past  election, when the airwaves were packed with attack ads, Hickenlooper was shown  jumping in and out of a shower, fully clothed. He said every time he saw a negative ad, he felt like he  needed to take a shower.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[Hickenlooper could afford to take a risk with his ads in this past election  because his two conservative opponents split the vote, giving him an easy win. But Hickenlooper's image and his  style of governing could become important as state leaders tackle Colorado's  looming budget gap.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA["I think he has a little bit of the  Teflon that Ronald Reagan enjoyed," says Colorado State University political  science professor John Straayer. "Things sort of slide off of him, and I think  that's largely because he's very affable, slow to anger, and I think that makes  him particularly effective."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Hickenlooper's effectiveness will be tested, though.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[A Budget In Crisis]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[The state already had to use  cuts and creative juggling to balance its budget. Federal stimulus money is  running out, and Colorado's expenses will rise faster than revenue in coming  years.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[As a Democrat, Hickenlooper also faces a reinvigorated Republican opposition. The GOP took  control of the lower house in the state General Assembly in November. The new  speaker, Republican state Rep. Frank McNulty, is a conservative who  talks about making government live within its means.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA["The savings account is gone. The rich  uncle that has been giving us money is not there anymore," says McNulty. "The  circumstances dictate a much higher level of belt tightening than they have even  in the past."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[No one is talking about tax increases in Colorado.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[There are a variety of  constraints voters have put on political leaders over the years that make it  difficult for them to do much aside from making cuts. And that's going to hurt.  Already, one-third of the school districts are on four-day weeks to save money,  higher education funding in Colorado ranks near the bottom of some lists, and  there's a backlog of infrastructure projects.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[The Mr. Nice Guy Strategy]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[Hickenlooper's strategy to deal with all this: Be a nice guy. He says that's a  lesson he learned in childhood that he will employ at the state Capitol.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA["My dad died when I was a  kid, and I had a year in elementary school where everybody hated me," says Hickenlooper. "I just kind of shot off my mouth, and I was just trying to make  people like me, but I did all the wrong things."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[Hickenlooper  says his mother created a chart, and every day when he got home from school, she  asked him if he'd said anything mean behind someone's back or been  disrespectful.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[''I'd get either a gold star, a silver  star or a red star," says Hickenlooper. "And it made me think about how you  relate with people and what it is that aggravates them."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[Hickenlooper says he'll spend a lot of time listening to people, trying to  figure out what they really want -- "and try to find where is that sweet spot  where, perhaps, no one is perfectly happy,'' he says. "But everyone feels that  they've gotten most of what they need.'']]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA[Given Colorado's fiscal crisis, while Hickenlooper may hope for a gold star, he  may be lucky to get a silver.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132813479">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/12/132813479/post-gm-model-envisioned-for-new-york-town?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132813479&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/f4mXHd</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Post-GM Model Envisioned For New York Town]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132813479&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132853972" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>222</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132853972-e0b11e.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132853972&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132853972&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[In northern New York, General Motors and the federal government have the challenging task of cleaning up a toxic site at one of the auto giant's former plants.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Massena, N.Y., is receiving the largest chunk of a nearly $800 million settlement that the bankruptcy estate of GM -- known as "Old GM" -- must commit toward cleaning up its contaminated properties. The settlement is a condition of the federal government helping to give the auto giant new life.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Massena used to be a big factory town, home to Alcoa, Reynolds and GM plants. But aluminum operations downsized, and when GM closed its powertrain plant last year, 500 jobs were lost.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[Massena's newly elected mayor, James Hidy, says Main Street used to be vibrant back in the 1970s, when he was an employee at the General Motors plant.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA["I moved to Detroit, transferred to Detroit, and moved back after 25 years, and it's just not the town it was. Obviously General Motors has left. Everything downsized. We don't have the population we had anymore, and with that, we don't have the vibrant downtown and storefronts that we used to have," Hidy says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[A regional task force is charged with figuring out how the sparsely populated community can cope with the loss of GM's plant, one the area's biggest economic drivers.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA["When you pick up the newspaper or you turn on the TV, and you see someone from GM with a big smile on their face, patting themselves on the back on how well they're doing, and you're the person living in the community with the EPA Superfund site and all your people laid off, it's a little hard to be as happy," says Patrick Turbett, who heads that task force.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[General Motors now makes headlines about public stock offerings and electric cars. Turbett's community watches all that from afar as they're stuck with Old GM -- officially named Motors Liquidation Company -- which was created from the bankruptcy restructuring to shed assets, including the former Massena plant.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[The plant's Superfund designation means it has hazardous substances in the soil. Anne Kelly, who oversees the Massena property for the Environmental Protection Agency, says because of that and several other reasons, the building will be demolished.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA["The facility is very outdated," Kelly says. At 50 years old, the building itself has become a hazard.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA["Chemicals that have been used -- paints, mercury switches, asbestos -- there are a number of contaminants that are incidental to manufacturing that will be a waste stream from this facility," Kelly says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[Kelly says the demolition of the 800,000-square-foot building -- the size of a really big mall -- will take almost two years.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[The Massena site is getting the largest share -- 15 percent -- of the $773 million trust fund. The rest of the money will go to more than a dozen states from the Eastern seaboard to the Midwest, as well as the St. Regis Mohawk tribal land, which butts up against the Massena property.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[After the demolition is finished, the county will try to market the 270 acres.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[But Mayor Hidy says he doesn't expect to land another big manufacturer that can bring 1,000 or 2,000 jobs.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA["I look at it as a new chapter for Massena. Manufacturing as we knew it yesterday is just not here throughout the U.S.," Hidy says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[That new chapter for Massena begins this month, when crews will begin scrubbing down the former GM plant to get rid of toxic dust in preparation for the demolition. The EPA says there will be enough money to clean up that site and others in the settlement. But just because those lands are restored doesn't mean all the environmental damage from former GM factories is resolved. The federal government still has roughly 45 unsettled claims of besmirched landscapes that could require cleanup.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
  </list>
</nprml>
