    <story id="132705352">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/06/132705352/david-wax-museum-tiny-desk-concert?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132705352&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/hfWxws</link>
      <title><![CDATA[David Wax Museum: Tiny Desk Concert]]></title>
      <audio id="132783329" type="primary">
        <title>Audio Only: David Wax Museum's Tiny Desk Concert</title>
        <duration>792</duration>
        <description>null</description>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132783329-9a21d4.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1110&amp;aggIds=92071316&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132783329&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1110&amp;aggIds=92071316&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132783329&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1110&amp;aggIds=92071316&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[I first saw the fun and frenetic David Wax Museum at the Newport Folk Festival this past summer -- the band had won a contest that got it to Newport. Its  blend of American and Mexican folk music was infectious, and by the show's end I  was already a fan. But when the festival was over, and the Newport  crew and musicians had gathered on a nearby roof to share some smiles and beer, there they  were again: David Wax with his pint-sized Mexican jarocha guitar and Suz  Slezak with her percussive donkey jawbone, making pure, irresistible joy.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Wax and Slezak recently came to the Tiny Desk with friends Sam D'Agostino on  saxophone and percussion and Mike Roberts on guitar and upright bass. (That  popping sound around a minute into "Yes, Marie, Yes" is the sound of  his bass bridge collapsing.) Not since Gogol Bordello's visit has it been so hard to keep a band in frame,  on mic and within the roughly six-square-foot area that functions as our performance space.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[David Wax Museum's album Everything Is Saved comes out on Feb. 8, and when the band returns to D.C., I'll definitely see it again. This kind of acoustic exuberance doesn't happen often enough.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132684525">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/06/132684525/rick-scott-floridas-outsider-is-now-in-office?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132684525&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/hWkR7C</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Gov. Scott, Ex-CEO, Aims To Run Fla. Like A Business]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132684525&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132699374" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>268</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132699374-14a3ea.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132699374&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132699374&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Washington, D.C., isn't the only place where political leadership is changing after last November's election. It's also changing in state capitals across the nation, where 29 new governors are taking office. Several were sworn in this week -- including in Florida, where Republican Rick Scott takes over from Republican turned independent Charlie Crist.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Unlike in California and New York, where festivities were toned down in a nod to the economy, Florida's inaugural events bordered on the lavish.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Scott's celebration stretched over two days and included a parade, dinners, breakfasts and a ball. The price tag? Some $3 million -- mostly raised from lobbyists and business interests.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[It's been a tough few years in Florida. The housing collapse has made the state a national leader in foreclosures. Unemployment is at 12 percent -- 2 points above the national average.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[At his inauguration, held outside Florida's old state capitol in Tallahassee, Scott told Floridians he's ready to make good on his campaign slogan: "Let's Get to Work."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA["Once we take the right steps," he said, "I am absolutely convinced that Florida will become the most exciting place in the world to live and work."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Placing An Emphasis On Business]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[Scott is a millionaire and the former CEO of the nation's largest for-profit hospital chain, Columbia/HCA. Shortly after he stepped down, the company paid the largest fine for Medicare fraud ever assessed. He won the governor's race by running as an outsider -- spending some $70 million of his own money.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[He has promised to streamline government and weed out unnecessary regulations. In his inaugural address, Scott said the government should be lean -- and do little more than provide a safety net. "Prosperity," he said, "comes from the private sector."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[Even before he ran for governor, Scott was an outspoken critic of President Obama and the new health care law. In his inaugural address, he said, "Faced with a deep recession, some say the answer is to expand the role of government. That's the approach the administration is taking in Washington. That is absolutely the wrong approach."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[Scott's first challenge as governor will be to come up with a budget that closes Florida's $3 billion budget deficit. To do so, he has floated a raft of ideas -- many of them controversial.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[He wants to cut the state workforce by 5 percent. He has vowed to slash $1 billion from the state prisons, and to reform the state's pension system.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Scott has also promised to phase out Florida's business income tax and to slash property taxes. He'll be aided by the fact that Florida's Legislature is controlled by Republicans -- many of whom share his governing philosophy.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[But Lance deHaven-Smith, a political science professor at Florida State University, says finding the money for all that won't be easy. "We've got a budget that's really lean as it is," he says. "Many of the obligations we have are things you can't just undo. You're not going to do away with Medicaid or something like that. Even small changes are difficult there. So I just have a question in my mind about how realistic these plans are."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[A Recent Arrival, Now Running Florida]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[As a first-time officeholder who moved to Florida only eight years ago, Scott is still an enigma to many in the state. With his election, he proved that he has determination, money and strong convictions. Floridians now wait to hear his agenda.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[He has said, for instance, that he wants to expand Florida's small school-voucher program to include all of the state's students -- a proposal tried on a smaller scale by former Gov. Jeb Bush, and which the courts found unconstitutional.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[Coming after four years of the moderate Charlie Crist, Scott is returning Florida to conservative leadership reminiscent of the Jeb Bush era.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[At Scott's inauguration, Bush acknowledged that the two men have similar views about government. Of Scott, Bush said, "He's an instinctive conservative. He doesn't start with the premise that the government's role is to solve a problem if there's another way to do it."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA[Scott has said he'll run government like a business. He is already finding that doing so presents its own challenges. To staff his administration, he has looked mostly to the private sector, but he has had problems filling many of the jobs -- in part because of the lower government pay scale.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA[After first requesting their resignations, Scott has asked hundreds of Crist administration staffers to stay on for a few more months while he searches for replacements.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132704459">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/06/132704459/billy-taylor-on-jazzset?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132704459&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/gXnFMH</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Billy Taylor On JazzSet]]></title>
      <audio id="132704999" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>3479</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132704999-013d44.m3u?orgId=314&amp;topicId=1109&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132704999&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=314&amp;topicId=1109&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132704999&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=314&amp;topicId=1109&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Dr. Billy Taylor -- affectionately "Billy" or "Dr. T" -- died on Dec. 28, 2010. He was the original host of NPR's Jazz Alive! from 1977 to '82, as well as the voice of live New Year's Eve broadcasts, loved for his engaged, enthusiastic, tutorial style. Then, as an Arts Correspondent for CBS Sunday Morning, Taylor added visuals. He would visit musicians at home, in the studio, teaching, running into each other with hugs and high fives. Jazz had been underground and marginal in the media. The light of Billy Taylor's smile, open mics and rolling cameras signaled a new era.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[This was his second great era. Earlier, he was the house pianist at Birdland (1949-50) and accompanied Art Tatum -– the astounding improviser and harmonizer who could not see -- around New York. Taylor was the bandleader for The David Frost Show on TV and host of local jazz shows on WLIB and WNEW. He led his trio, composed and recorded. His song, "I Wish I Knew How It Would Feel to Be Free," was covered by Nina Simone and others. Dr. T earned his doctorate at the University of Massachusetts-Amherst, with a dissertation on jazz piano styles that he adapted to radio as Taylor-Made Piano from NPR. There was also a book, which I used as a reference for years.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Until his death, Taylor was the long-running Artistic Director for Jazz at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. He was the heart of the connection between the Kennedy Center and JazzSet. We feel great appreciation for his leadership and friendship.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[To remember him, we will rebroadcast "Billy Taylor's Diz," his retirement concert from March 31, 2005, at the Kennedy Center. To no one's surprise, Taylor stayed busy and active after this occasion. And, as his musical guest notes from the stage, Taylor does not sound like a retiree; he sounds lively and delighted to play.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[For the concert, Taylor invited trumpeter Jon Faddis to share the stage and to celebrate their mutual friend Dizzy Gillespie (1917-93). Between tunes, Faddis describes meeting Diz. When he was 15, Faddis brought his entire Gillespie collection of LPs to the Monterey Jazz Festival, where Gillespie patiently autographed each one, claiming not to remember several of them.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Taylor credits Gillespie for moving jazz closer to Latin music and advancing jazz harmony. Gillespie compositions are the heart of this set. Then, at the end, Taylor closes with "Take the 'A' Train," played very slowly, at the tempo he discovered when he played the tune at composer Billy Strayhorn's funeral.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[To open, we hear an earlier Taylor trio from WBGO in Newark. In the late 1980s, the station acquired a new Steinway piano and asked Taylor to inaugurate it. He promised to play every key, and he does -- fast, flowing, accurate and with ease -- during "The Man I Love."  [Copyright 2011 WBGO-FM]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132692084">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/06/132692084/congresss-celebration-complete-sniping-resumes?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132692084&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/eJy4aD</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Congress' Celebration Complete, Sniping Resumes]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132692084&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132699297" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>253</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132699297-83351b.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132699297&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132699297&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1014&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Republicans roared into the majority in the House of Representatives on Wednesday, swearing in new members and giving a standing ovation to the new Speaker John Boehner (R-OH).]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Outgoing Speaker Nancy Pelosi (D-CA) turned over a super-sized gavel to Boehner, along with "the sacred trust that goes with it."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[The mood was light, but Boehner acknowledged that there is a great deal of what he called "scar tissue" from partisan warfare. He said one way to reduce the tension is to give everyone more time.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA["Mindful of the lessons of the past ... legislators and the public will have three days to read a bill before it comes to a vote," he said. "Legislation will be properly scrutinized and actually sound. Committees, once bloated, will be smaller with a renewed mission."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[But legislation set to come to the floor seems likely to kick off new battles. Democrats are complaining about rules mandating spending cuts and about the GOP's refusal to open up the planned health care overhaul repeal to amendments.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Across the Capitol, the new Senate opened for business under continued Democratic control, although with a smaller margin.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Majority Leader Harry Reid (D-NV) came back with an eye to changing the rules governing filibusters, which tend to benefit the minority. He wants to limit damage to his party's agenda from increasing threats -- often made anonymously -- to talk bills and nominations to death.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA["We may not agree yet on how to fix the problem, but no one can credibly claim problems don't exist," he said. "No one who has watched this body operate since the current majority took office can say that it functions just fine."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Sen. Claire McCaskill (D-MO) is one of the senators battling anonymous obstructions.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA["Nothing is more hypocritical than all the sanctimonious stuff I'm hearing down the hall about the new era, no more business as usual ... [and] we're going to have accountability and transparency. But yet we seem to be embroiled down on this end of the hall with not even being able to get beyond a secret hold," she lamented.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[For his part, Reid is hoping another parliamentary maneuver will help him get a handle on filibusters. He technically extended the legislative day over the next few weeks, to take advantage of the narrow window when a simple majority is all it takes to change the rules.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[Minority Leader Mitch McConnell of Kentucky warned him that Democrats could come to regret losing the secret hold if they lose the majority and "suddenly find themselves completely powerless to prevent Republicans from overturning legislation they themselves have worked so hard to enact."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[McConnell's other argument is that the Senate functions as it is supposed to.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA["The founders crafted the Senate to be different," he said. "They crafted it to be a deliberate, thoughtful place, and changing the rules in the way that's been proposed would unalterably change the Senate itself."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[The Senate has left Washington but will return in a few weeks.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[The House is in session Thursday, with the new speaker having ordered a reading of the U.S. Constitution. He also hopes to get in votes to repeal the health care overhaul and the first round of spending cuts before President Obama's State of the Union address at the end of the month.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132490242">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2011/01/01/132490242/boomers-take-the-retire-out-of-retirement?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132490242&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/dMucT3</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Boomers Take The  'Retire' Out Of Retirement]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132490242&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132551179" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>691</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132551179-fd6aad.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1028&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132551179&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1028&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132551179&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1028&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[It may be hard to believe, but the generation that transformed America as it came of age in the 1960s is now entering its senior years.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA["There are 7,000 boomers a day who will be turning 65 in 2011, which is a significant birthday for sure," says Steve Cone, executive vice president of AARP.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Sixty-five used to be the age when Americans stopped working, kicked back and embarked on serious leisure to make up for all those decades of the daily grind. But just like with every other stage of life they've gone through, baby boomers are expected to transform how we think about "retirement."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[Leading the way will be couples like Stephanie and Stan Zirkin. She will turn 65 on May 14; he's already 65, not officially a boomer, but, as he puts it, "close enough."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[The Zirkins live in a cozy rowhouse in the Washington, D.C., suburb of Greenbelt, Md. Since their daughter split from her husband, Stephanie has stepped in as a main caregiver for her 6-year-old grandson, Stephen.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA["To be perfectly frank," she says, "by the time Stephen came along, I was kind of tired out."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[When her daughter is working, Stephanie picks up Stephen at the bus stop after school, supervises homework and sometimes feeds him dinner.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA["I always wanted to have a grandchild that I could take care of on a daily basis," she says. "I just hadn't pictured it happening that far along."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Boomers may have bolted for the door at 18 and been off their parents' payroll after college, but their offspring are taking longer to reach traditional milestones of adulthood. Marriage and children come later. Certainly with the bad economy, some are taking longer to establish careers. Growing numbers of 20-somethings have been moving back in with their boomer parents after college, a loving form of financial subsidy.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[When the Zirkins' daughter separated from her husband, Stan found another way to help out.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA["I dipped into my savings and bought her a condominium, which is a hundred yards from here," he says. "You know, I was feeling very secure when I ended my mortgage a few years ago, but now I have another one!"]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[Working Longer]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Stan is a branch chief at the National Labor Relations Board, commuting via car and Metro to downtown Washington each day. He says he loves his work, and despite reaching traditional retirement age, he isn't about to give it up.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA["I've spent my entire career doing good for people who might otherwise be powerless," he says. "That's a feeling I can't imagine being duplicated anyplace else."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[Stan was eligible for retirement a decade ago. When friends ask if he's considering it, Stephanie has a ready answer:]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA["Not till they pry the [subway] farecard from his cold, dead fingers!" she says, laughing.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[That, too, is typical. Boomers, more educated than their parents, may derive more of their identity through work.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[In an AARP poll of people hitting 65 this year, Cone says, 40 percent have no intention of retiring.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA["The 40 percent is a much larger group than any generation before the boomers," he says. "But the other factor we see in the poll is that a lot of people feel they have to keep working."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA[In fact, when AARP asked what the best 65th birthday gift would be, the top answer was "financial security."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA[The recent recession derailed retirement plans for many. But Alicia Munnell, of the Center for Retirement Research at Boston College, says the problem goes beyond that.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA["We are having a contraction in all aspects of the retirement income system," she says, "so boomers are going to face a much tougher time than their parents faced."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="23"><![CDATA[Living Longer]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="24"><![CDATA[A 2009 study by the center found that 51 percent of working households today will be unable to maintain their standard of living once they retire. The reasons are many.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="25"><![CDATA[Munnell says because of the rising retirement age and the tax structure, Social Security is replacing less and less of a beneficiary's earnings. Traditional pensions are disappearing, replaced by riskier 401(k)s. Then there's the exploding cost of health care and the shrinking value of homes. There's also the fact, Munnell says, that Americans simply do not save enough. On top of all this, everyone's living much longer.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="26"><![CDATA["What we are trying to do is have people save for a 40-year work life for 20 years in retirement," Munnell says. "The arithmetic doesn't work out if you think about it. People just don't get enough income during that period."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="27"><![CDATA[In fact, for those who retire early, it's entirely possible today to spend more years in retirement than you did in your job. Munnell believes those who can should work longer. She'd also like to see another government-sponsored program to encourage retirement savings.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="28"><![CDATA[Longevity is certainly an issue for Stephanie and Stan Zirkin; each has a parent in his 90s.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="29"><![CDATA["My father is 97," says Stephanie. "He lives alone. He's still got all his marbles, maybe even acquired another few. He's tough."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="30"><![CDATA[The Zirkins say their parents are still financially independent. And, unlike many, they feel they have saved well for retirement. Stephanie believes their sense of thrift may speak more to their Depression-era parents than the rest of her generation.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="31"><![CDATA[Still, looking after aging parents on one end and struggling children on the other is probably no one's retirement dream. And yet, Cone says, the AARP survey shows an extraordinary -- and characteristic -- resilience.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="32"><![CDATA["Boomers feel very optimistic about a) their future, and b) what they've accomplished," he says. Some 80 percent reported that they are happy where they are in life.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="33"><![CDATA[Retirement Alternatives]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="34"><![CDATA[Stan says he's followed with interest some of his contemporaries who've already retired. He's found no one moving to Florida to sit by a pool.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="35"><![CDATA["One of the guys decided he majored in the wrong subject in college so he's back in college," Stan says. "He's taking anthropology, I think. That's his new love, and he says he intends to stay until he gets another degree, just for the heck of it.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="36"><![CDATA["Another one, he always wanted to work with his hands, and so he used some of his retirement money to purchase rundown houses, and he's renovating them himself.  So, they are not retiring. They are simply going to a different stage of their life."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="37"><![CDATA[Stephanie says this is fine by her; no need to have Stan lounging around the house all day. And really, she's busy enough caring for her grandson.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="38"><![CDATA[So what is she looking forward to in coming decades?  "Ooh," she smiles, "great-grandchildren!"  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132444322">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2010/12/30/132444322/change-you-can-invest-in-social-entrepreneurship?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132444322&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/hfk6Fg</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Change You Can Invest In: Social Entrepreneurship]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132444322&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132464819" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>293</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132464819-71936b.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;aggIds=130593764&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132464819&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;aggIds=130593764&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132464819&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;aggIds=130593764&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[The past decade or so has seen explosive growth in the number of social entrepreneurs -- innovators who take a business-like approach to solving social problems. NPR is profiling a number of these people this year.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[NPR's Larry Abramson looks at how the movement has matured -- it's even becoming a full-fledged academic discipline.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[On a recent evening, a few dozen people gathered at a Washington, D.C., restaurant to share food, drinks -- and ideas on how to attack some of the biggest problems on the planet, such as hunger in Africa and health care in India.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[But this group isn't made up of big-time diplomats or bureaucrats. Many head small organizations they started themselves.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[The attendees were brought together by Ashoka, an organization that has been helping entrepreneurs launch themselves for 30 years. Among the attendees is a man who hopes to join this exclusive club.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Advocating For Music In Schools]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[David Wish, in his 40s with salt-and-pepper hair, is not fighting hunger or disease. But he is just as passionate about addressing another problem: the disappearance of music education from public schools. His organization, Little Kids Rock, is active in 26 cities. It helps provide instruments and music instruction to kids, at no cost to the schools.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[Wish is already a seasoned social entrepreneur, but he wants to become an Ashoka fellow. And it's not because of the cash award. Instead, he wants to be part of the network of fellows devoted to social innovation.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA["Being in the presence of people who have devoted their life's work to that is really an inspiring thing," he says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[Ashoka has been nurturing social innovators for 30 years. People usually become fellows only after their organizations have proven their value and distinguished themselves in the nonprofit world. But as the sector has grown, new groups have begun stoking the fires on the supply side, teaching the value of social innovation to young people.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[Incubating Ideas In The Classroom]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[According to one estimate, 500 professors are teaching courses on social entrepreneurship worldwide. On a recent day at the University of Maryland, students took their seats for the final class in a course called "Transformative Action: Effective Methods for Social Change."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Part of the business school's Center for Social Value Creation, it requires students to come up with a viable business idea by the end of the semester.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[One student, John MacDonald, wears a yellow striped tie and a nervous smile for his group's presentation. The Leaf Academy is the group's idea for a charter school that would teach kids about the outdoors.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA["Imagine a world where children play together outside," MacDonald tells his fellow students, "where they are given an opportunity to experience nature around us."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[It's a nice idea, but would anyone fund it? To find out, the university has brought in two nonprofit venture capitalists, guys who help fund social ventures in the real world.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[Steve Lynott, with an outfit called the 1901 Group, listens patiently to their ideas, and then responds.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA["My big recommendation to you," he says, "is [to] narrow the aperture. Find a particular problem in schools that you want to look at. Right now it's just a bit too broad."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[After class ends, the other venture capitalist in the room, Drew Bewick of Tree House Ventures, says that just like traditional businesses, many social startups stall because they don't see themselves as a business.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA["I see a lot of them fail after a year, because they didn't think of that sustainable piece," he says. "They're almost afraid to describe it as a business model."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA[For New Nonprofits, New Donors]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA[Some of the new growth in social entrepreneurship may be coming from donors themselves. Many people with money to give away don't want to hand it over to foundations, who then dole it out as they choose.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="23"><![CDATA[Chuck Harris is a former executive with Goldman Sachs who's now working with social entrepreneurs. He says that over the past decade, the wealthy began turning to independent thinkers with new approaches to social problems.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="24"><![CDATA["You were starting to see first-generation philanthropists who didn't inherit the money had made it themselves," he says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="25"><![CDATA[These donors follow their own pattern of giving. Harris says that many of them "hoped to find the same kind of support for their decision-making in philanthropy that is readily available in the for-profit investment world."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="26"><![CDATA[Harris felt the same frustration. So he left Goldman Sachs and founded his own nonprofit, SeaChange Capital Partners. Now he's helping other social innovators run their operations more like traditional businesses. Harris says his advice could include looking more like a corporation, with a board of directors.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="27"><![CDATA[That's a step many are reluctant to take. But many nonprofits fail without good oversight. Gary Snyder, with the watchdog group Nonprofit Imperative, says that because social enterprises rely heavily on trust, they're prone to fraud.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="28"><![CDATA["Anybody close to the money is typically untrained and not monitored," he says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="29"><![CDATA[Some observers say that social entrepreneurs' deep sense of mission can easily blind them to that and other risks.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132267994">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/blogs/pictureshow/2010/12/24/132267994/visiting-kabuls-old-city?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132267994&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/dIsjtJ</link>
      <title><![CDATA[In Afghanistan, Visiting Kabul's Old City]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132267994&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132304283" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>467</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132304283-2be501.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1149&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132304283&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1149&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132304283&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1149&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Venturing deep into the corners and warrens of Kabul's Old City, we stepped over gullies of exposed sewer pipes and tip-toed around an open swath of earth where men were laying the foundation for a new building.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Airborne sawdust coated my microphones. The sounds of hard work were everywhere: iron hammers, the roll of rusty wheelbarrows, the shouts of men, the trickle of a water pump, the pull of mud on boots and sandals.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[There in a small part of Kabul's Old City called Murad Khane, centuries-old homes and courtyards were being restored. Long ago, craftsmen had carved these structures out of wood. Years of war and poverty and neglect had left the place all-but-withered and full of trash.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[New builders were there now, backed by the non-profit Turquoise Mountain Foundation. The effort is trying -- quickly -- to restore this portion of Kabul's dignity and history before it is lost forever.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[We were in awe of their astonishingly well-crafted work.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Until we met Haidarab.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[He supervises a portion of a renovation project -- and as soon as he told us his family had been living in Murad Khane for generations, the art of the old wood around us became a lot less interesting.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[Haidarab's ancestors were the very ones who came to this city centuries before. They were the jewelers and tailors and others who'd been imported from Afghanistan's hinterlands to serve an early king. The Old City had been built for them so they'd be close to the king's beck and call.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Haidarab's forebears had been among those servants of the ancient court.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[And -- yet again in Afghanistan -- I was learning about the country's ancient history from the face (and the smile) of a man standing before me.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132260323">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2010/12/24/132260323/one-students-christmas-lesson?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132260323&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/fa63Cy</link>
      <title><![CDATA[One Student's Christmas Lesson]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132260323&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132304294" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>118</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132304294-edeb99.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1022&amp;aggIds=4516989&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132304294&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1022&amp;aggIds=4516989&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132304294&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1022&amp;aggIds=4516989&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Don Michaels really didn't like school for a while when he was growing up.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA["I had terrible migraine headaches when I was in fifth grade," he explained to his daughter Jennifer recently. "Whether that was because of the pressure, or because of the reputation that the teacher at the time had, and my having gotten reports from my three brothers who had her, I just, I just don't know."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Michaels remembers his teacher, Miss Leister, having very sharp features.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA["The most prominent thing was her nose -- it was very hawkish," the 72-year-old said. "She didn't smile a great deal. And she was a taskmaster -- she expected you to perform."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[Miss Leister wasn't very warm, he said.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA["But we had a Christmas party -- all the classes had Christmas parties -- and we all exchanged names for gifts. And the Christmas party started, the gifts were being handed out, names were being called, and one by one all my classmates went up to get their gift. When the gifts were all gone, I had not been called and did not receive a gift, for some reason or other."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[The day before Christmas, Miss Leister showed up at Michaels' house, unannounced.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA["And she had a small gift that she gave to me," he said. "That gift was a key chain. I kept that for years and years. And as odd as it may seem, my headaches went away about two days after she came."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Michaels' relationship with Miss Leister changed from that day on.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[Produced for Morning Edition by Jasmyn Belcher. The senior producer for StoryCorps is Michael Garofalo. Recorded in partnership with WPSU.    [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="132152168">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2010/12/18/132152168/groups-care-packages-aim-to-lift-troop-spirits?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=132152168&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/fwFFvQ</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Group's Care Packages Aim To Lift Troops' Spirits]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=132152168&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132162150" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>314</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132162150-da108c.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;aggIds=131390872&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132162150&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;aggIds=131390872&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132162150&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1091&amp;aggIds=131390872&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Carolyn Blashek founded Operation Gratitude in 2003 -- the year the Iraq war started. The volunteer-based organization sends care packages to the troops, that include handwritten letters and handmade scarves.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Blashek, who has two children, says she was inspired to start the organization by the idea that a service member thousands of miles from home might feel forgotten.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[This year Operation Gratitude sent out its 600,000th package.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA['Sometimes We Feel Forgotten']]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[The first thing you notice about Blashek's kitchen are the pictures of men and women in uniform, mostly camouflage. They adorn the cupboards and one entire wall. The kitchen counter is covered with mail. The first letter she opens is from a Marine in Afghanistan.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"/>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Everyone was so excited when we got the packages. We read through all the letters, shared them together and we were all just so happy.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"/>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[The thank you letters she receives are handwritten -- sometimes on lined paper, a single piece of stationary, even a torn piece of cardboard. The message is nearly always the same.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"/>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[You have no idea how much one little box filled with random goodies can brighten a service member's day.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[Dear Operation Gratitude: On behalf of myself and my entire air traffic control detachment here in Afghanistan I want to thank you for all the wonderful care packages we have been receiving. Not everyone here receives mail that often and sometimes we feel forgotten.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"/>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[Blashek has kept all these thank you letters, so many they fill a back room.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA["One was a letter I got from a soldier that he wrote back to me saying, 'At the end of the day I had eaten the food and watched the DVD, but there was a letter from a little girl in Michigan that meant so much to me that I folded it up. I put it in my helmet and it goes with me everywhere I go,'" Blashek recalls.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA['Dear Soldier']]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[This year, the headquarters for Operation Gratitude is a National Guard armory in Los Angeles where on a recent day hundreds of volunteers were preparing to ship the holiday packages. One corner of the armory looked like a post office annex.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[Linda Barber, a longtime volunteer, is in charge of the letters. The ones in crayon and bold print stand out -- maybe it's the glued-on sparkles. Barber, 72, says the letters from the kids often begin "Dear Soldier."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[Army Staff Sgt. Matthew Gomez received an Operation Gratitude package in 2007 while serving in Afghanistan. He's still on active duty and stationed at the armory.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA["It's just a good feeling to know someone else is thinking of you. Not a lot of us received mail or packages that came in the mail over there," he says. "For soldiers, it's a big deal, receiving something from back home."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA[A Stitch And A Prayer]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA[Every year, thousands of volunteers back home knit and crochet handmade scarves to go into the troop packages. One of those people is 98-year-old Joan Mazzarelli. She has platinum hair, a pixie smile and on her lap, is a pair of knitting needles.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="23"><![CDATA[Since March, Mazzarelli has knitted or crocheted 527 scarves and hats for what she calls her boys and girls in the war. There was another war being fought overseas when she first began this task in 1940, during World War II.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="24"><![CDATA["I knitted not only scarves, but socks and gloves, everything for the soldiers," Mazzarelli says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="25"><![CDATA[She had a beauty shop back then and would knit in-between customers. These days she knits about 14 hours a day.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="26"><![CDATA[Mazzarelli says the thank you letters she receives today are not that different than the ones she received 70 years ago.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="27"/>
        <paragraph num="28"><![CDATA[I just want to thank you for including your special gift of a handmade hat. I'm reminded of my grandma's crocheted hats she made for my sister and I when we were kids. ]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="29"/>
        <paragraph num="30"><![CDATA[But, as much as she loves knitting for the men and women deployed to Iraq and Afghanistan, Mazzarelli says she wishes they were home.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="31"><![CDATA[Until then, she'll continue knitting. For her, knitting is an act of service, a prayerful meditation.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="32"><![CDATA["A prayer with each stitch," she says.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="131938609">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2010/12/13/131938609/pain-persists-for-mine-disaster-family?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=131938609&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/eyrAyx</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Pain Persists For Mine Disaster Family]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=131938609&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="132032399" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>507</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1132032399-eacc06.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1150&amp;aggIds=131960177&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=132032399&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1150&amp;aggIds=131960177&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=132032399&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1150&amp;aggIds=131960177&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Eight months after the Upper Big Branch mine disaster, the families of the 29 coal miners who lost their lives continue to live in grief, yet few have described their pain publicly.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA["Here in southern West  Virginia [we] tend to keep that stuff closely held," said Randolph McGraw, a lawyer in Beckley, W Va., who represents the families of six Upper Big Branch victims.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA["[We] understand the risk … when something ultimately happens that is beyond the comprehension of people from other parts of the country," McGraw said.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[But Gene Jones believes speaking out is critical, especially as public memory of the tragedy fades. Jones, 50, lost his identical twin Dean in the explosion.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA["We're just going to be forgotten," Jones says, while mine disasters are "going to continue and continue and continue to go on. We need it fixed."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[So Jones agreed to describe his family's ordeal, hoping that mine safety regulators, state and federal investigators, the mining industry, Congress and Americans in general will be reminded of the human cost of the nation's worst mine disaster in 40 years.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA["They mourn for you," Jones notes, "and it's unbelievable how this nation came together. But if [we] don't speak out and continue to speak out, it's just forgotten."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[A Reflection Of The Loss]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Gene and Dean Jones were so close in their mother's womb doctors detected just a single heartbeat.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA["I was 10 minutes older than Dean," Gene said. "It's like part of me is gone."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA["I think about him every day," Gene said from a conference room at Appalachian Power in Beckley, where he works as an electrical engineer. His hazel eyes welled with tears. "So I work a lot not to think about it."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[An obituary Gene wrote for his brother that includes an image of Dean, broadly smiling, sits on the table. If it wasn't for Dean's mustache, the twins would look exactly alike.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Still, when Gene looks in the mirror he sees his brother.  "When people see me they see me and Dean," Gene adds, referring to Dean's widow Gina and their now 14-year-old son Kyle.  "When Kyle sees me he sees his daddy some and when he listens to me talk, he probably thinks, 'Whoa, that's my dad!'"]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[On April 5, Dean Jones went four miles inside the Upper Big Branch mine to an area called Headgate 22. Dean was a section boss and mining engineer with 30 years underground. He and his crew of eight miners were using a continuous mining machine to dig the entryways or tunnels needed to get the area ready for mining.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[Dean and Gene went to school together all the way through engineering studies. They shared three paper routes as kids and spoke in rapid conversations nobody else could understand. They both followed their late father Dallas into the mines and Dean loved it. But Gene couldn’t take the dusty, dark and confined conditions.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA["These men were doing something that nobody else wanted to do because it's a scary, dangerous job," Gene says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[The Disaster]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[While Dean was underground late that afternoon, Gene sat on his porch in Beckley about 20 miles away. He had just mailed his tax return at the post office, and was blissfully unaware of the emergency calls that started pouring in.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[When Gene's phone rang, his youngest sister Cheryl was on the line, frantic.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA["They had a mine explosion at Upper Big Branch," she told her brother.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA["You can't believe the feeling that went over me," Gene said. "It just scared me."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA[Dean's wife Gina and his sister Judy joined the miners' families gathering near the mine. Gene stayed with his 83-year-old mother to help her through the ordeal.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="23"><![CDATA["It went on for days waiting on whether Dean was alive or not," Gene remembers. "It was just awful."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="24"><![CDATA[It was eerily familiar. Families gathered for vigils and stayed glued to television news.  "It was just hard to believe that my family was looking at this, facing this," Gene says, "and wondering is my brother going to come out alive?"]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="25"><![CDATA[Dean's decades of mining experience and his location in the mine bolstered the family's hope.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="26"><![CDATA["I know that my brother was at the furthest point away from the explosion, a few hundred feet from the safety area" Judy told the Today show.  "He would have felt the concussion.  He would have felt the sucking of the air.  He would have known that that was possibly fatal for them and he would have taken his men to the safety area."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="27"><![CDATA[The safety area is a rescue chamber stocked with food, water and oxygen.  And even after rescue teams had found the bodies of most of the men on Dean's crew, there was hope that he and three others might be safe.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="28"><![CDATA[But shortly after midnight on April 10, five days after the blast, Judy and Gina burst through the door with the terrible news.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="29"><![CDATA[Gene describes the scene, sighing deeply between words and sentences.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="30"><![CDATA["Gina was screaming and hollering, saying 'I couldn't bring him home. I just couldn't do it.'  And then I knew he was gone," Gene remembers. "And it was just chaotic at the house, just crazy.  And we all just broke down and cried."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="31"><![CDATA[Later, the Jones family was told that Dean was gone in an instant. The blast hit him face first and came back and hit him again as the concussive forces bounced around in the confined spaces underground.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="32"><![CDATA[As an engineer, Gene knows what those forces can do. "He was like a rag doll," Gene says. "Use your imagination." The condition of Dean's body, he suggests, is too horrible to describe.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="33"><![CDATA[Seeking A Safe Future]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="34"><![CDATA[With the holidays coming, Gene anticipates gloomy family gatherings. "It's really hard to think about that," he says. "We never dreamed he would not be here. It's so unexpected. So now we're having to deal with it."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="35"><![CDATA[Gene's sadness turns to anger and frustration as he recalls Dean's complaints about safety problems at Upper Big Branch. Alice Peters, Dean's mother-in-law, testified in a congressional hearing in Beckley in May that Dean had been threatened with dismissal seven times because he resisted putting his crew in danger.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="36"><![CDATA["Dean needed his job to make sure his son could get the medical care he needed," Peters testified. That's a reference to Kyle's cystic fibrosis and the health insurance Dean's job provided.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="37"><![CDATA[Peters also told the congressional committee that Dean's wife does not go out unless Peters is with her, "and then she just cries the entire time."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="38"><![CDATA[Kyle turned down his father's bed sheets at night, Gene notes, and sometimes crawled in with Dean so the two would be together before it was time to get up for work.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="39"><![CDATA[Gene considers his own son, who also works in a coal mine.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="40"><![CDATA["I want to make sure that he comes home every day," he says. "And since this happened, I call my son every day at two o'clock or he calls me before he goes into the mine so I can hear his voice."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="41"><![CDATA[Gene reflects on the eight months since Dean Jones and 28 other brothers, fathers, sons and grandfathers died. Congress rejected mine safety reform, he says. The civil and criminal investigations of the Upper Big Branch explosion drag on. And he wonders about the value Massey Energy has placed on his brother's life. Departing CEO Don Blankenship, he notes, is getting a golden parachute worth at least $12 million -- four times the settlement the company offered to the Jones family.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="42"><![CDATA["It's so sad to hear these crazy things," he says. The miners "were there every day risking their lives for that black coal, for us, surviving in this country."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="43"><![CDATA[Gene Jones pauses with a massive sigh. "And because of that," he continues, "I lost my brother."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="44"><![CDATA[West   Virginia Public Broadcasting contributed to this report.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="131968314">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2010/12/10/131968314/remembering-james-moody-s-humble-gift-for-music?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=131968314&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/fFoBs7</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Remembering James Moody's Humble Gift For Music]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=131968314&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="131972554" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>243</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1131972554-f580c1.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1106&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=131972554&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1106&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=131972554&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1106&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Saxophonist James Moody died Thursday after a battle with pancreatic cancer. He was 85.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Moody's name and career are forever linked to "Moody's Mood for Love," the minor hit single that inspired singer Eddie Jefferson to set Moody's improvisation to lyrics. Van Morrison, George Benson and Queen Latifah are among at least a dozen artists who have covered the song.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[The jazz great was also known for his skillful, soulful improvisations on flute and various saxophones. Moody kept performing and touring until recently, when his illness made it impossible.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[Moody's life began with interesting challenges. In 1996, he told Terry Gross, host of WHYY's Fresh Air, that he was born partially deaf.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA["It doesn't mean that I have a speech impediment," Moody says. "It's just that I don't hear S's. Because my wife always tells me when I'm singing '[Moody's] Mood for Love,' I'd say, 'You give me a smile,' and it sounds like 'You give me a mile.' "]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Moody couldn't hear certain high notes as a child, but it didn't dampen his love for music. He listened to big bands -- especially the saxophonists -- on the radio.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Coveting The Saxophone]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[Moody told NPR in 1997 that he used to spend a lot of time standing outside the windows of his neighborhood music store in Newark, N.J.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA["I used to look at the saxophones every day," Moody said. "I'd just look at 'em, you know. And when I first got my first saxophone, I put it in bed by me and just used to sleep with it, man. Just looking at it."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[His uncle bought him a secondhand alto saxophone when he was 16.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[Moody mostly taught himself how to play the sax. His first real musical training came as a member of the Negro Air Force Band, an unofficial group formed in his segregated unit during World War II.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[Bebop legend Dizzy Gillespie heard him on a military base in North Carolina and hired him for his bebop big band after Moody was discharged. He played three years with Gillespie, but an early addiction problem sent him to recover at his uncle's home in Paris. Moody says a two-week trip to Paris turned into a three-year stay.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA['Moody's Mood For Love']]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[During that time, Moody recorded an album in Sweden and experienced a minor hit in 1949. He used a borrowed alto saxophone and improvised over the chord changes to the pop song "I'm in the Mood for Love." His improvisation never stated the melody and was released as "Moody's Mood for Love." It inspired a couple of jukebox hits based on his performance, as he explained to Marian McPartland on NPR's Piano Jazz in 1997.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[Singer Eddie Jefferson turned Moody's improvisation into words, and King Pleasure's version of the tune became an even bigger hit in 1952.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[Moody wasn't the singer heard on the records by Jefferson or King Pleasure, but "Moody's Mood for Love" became his calling card. He returned from Europe to the U.S. to capitalize on the popularity of the songs.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[Moody would lead his own groups and albums in the decades that followed. For the better part of the 1970s, he played in Las Vegas show bands and watched his daughter grow into a teenager. He would continue to work in jazz ensembles led by his lifelong friend and mentor Dizzy Gillespie, and he became known for sophisticated, soulful solos on flute, alto and tenor saxophones.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[He was respected by jazz musicians for constantly practicing and striving to improve himself as an artist. Trumpeter and educator Jon Faddis says he first met Moody when Faddis was a skinny teenager cracking corny knock-knock jokes around Oakland, Calif. Some 30 years later, Moody presided over Faddis' wedding in 2001 in a B'hai ceremony. Faddis says he's long admired both the artist and the man.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA["Younger musicians like Antonio Hart and myself will look at Moody and see someone who is always searching and learning more about music and life, and is always willing to share what he knows about music and life with others," Faddis says.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA[The Humble Genius]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA[Faddis says Moody's curiosity and nature were always childlike, and that Moody was both talented and humble about his gift.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA["He'll play a solo," Faddis says. "You're sitting there listening to it. You'll say, 'Wow,' and then Moody will come over to you on the side of the stage and say, 'Was that all right?' "]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="23"><![CDATA[Moody, a showman in concert, made his audiences laugh with his self-deprecating honesty.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="24"><![CDATA["And the thing about it, ladies and gentlemen, is this is the way I am," Moody told a crowd at the Kennedy Center in 1995. "If I make a mistake, like, that's me, because, you see, making mistakes is being perfect. I'm serious, because I'm perfectly me."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="25"><![CDATA[The Los Angeles Times reported that Moody's survivors include his wife of 21 years, Linda; a brother, Lou Watters; a daughter, Michelle Bagdanove; sons Patrick, Regan and Danny McGowan; four grandchildren; and one great-grandson.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="26"><![CDATA[Moody played at the White House for three different sitting presidents and was nominated for four Grammy awards, including one for his most recent album, Moody 4B.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="131958862">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2010/12/10/131958862/fresh-air-remembers-saxophonist-james-moody?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=131958862&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/gMTuxK</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Fresh Air Remembers Saxophonist James Moody]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=131958862&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="131933747" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>1180</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1131933747-c1ff58.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1105&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=131933747&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1105&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=131933747&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1105&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"/>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[Jazz saxophonist and flutist James Moody, who began his career playing bebop with Dizzy Gillespie's Big Band and recorded for more than 60 years, died Thursday. He was 85.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[Moody first became known for his 1949 recording of the song "I'm in the Mood for Love." His reworking of the melody was so powerful, it became the melody for a new song with lyrics by Eddie Jefferson, called "Moody's Mood for Love."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[That song began, "There I go, there I go, there I go..." and became a standard for both Moody and other jazz singers. In a 1996 interview on Fresh Air, he described the impact "Moody's Mood" -- which was named to the Grammy Hall of Fame in 2001 -- had on the rest of his career.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA["If I don't do it to this day,' he said, "people say I haven't been there. That goes to show you, no matter how much I practice, if I don't say, 'There I go, there I go,' then it's like I haven't been there. ... I love doing it, and it's been very good to me, that solo. And I'm honored and privileged, I believe, to be able to do it."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Moody began his career in 1947, in the early days of bebop, playing with Dizzy Gillespie's Big Band. By the end of the '40s, he'd left the group and moved to Europe. He returned to the U.S. in the early '50s to lead his own band -- and played with Gillespie again for much of the '60s. But in the '70s, Moody left the jazz scene to work a steady job in a Vegas hotel band. When he returned to the jazz world in the late '70s, critic Gary Giddins wrote that "there were few living musicians [he] enjoyed hearing perform more than Moody."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[In 1998, the National Endowment for the Arts named Moody a Jazz Master. His last album, Moody 4B, was released in 2010.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"/>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Interview Highlights]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[On His Voice]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"/>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA["I'm not as concerned with my voice as I am with my lisp that I have, you know, because I'm partially deaf.  And I was born that way, and it doesn't mean that I have a speech impediment; it's just that I don't hear S's.  My wife always tells me, when I'm singing "Mood for Love," I'd say, 'You give me a smile,' and it sounds like you're saying, 'You give me a mile.' "]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[On Serving In The Air Force In A Segregated Unit]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"/>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA["I was 18 years old, right, and I was living in Newark, New Jersey. Do you know that the German prisoners of war used to come into town and jump off the truck, you know -- with the PW on their back and those hats -- and go into the restaurants and eat and we couldn't?"]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[On Being In The Room When Dizzy Gillespie Died]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"/>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA["There were five of us in there with him when he passed. And you know what's funny?  I told [another person in the room], I said, 'You mark my word, 10 years from now, there are going to be 50 people in the room with Dizzy Gillespie,' you know?  You know?  And there was no music playing.  There was nothing.  I mean, Diz was just -- he was just sitting there but, you know, trying to breathe deep, trying to get his breath.  And his eyes were closed, you know what I mean?  And, yes, he never opened them, and finally he took the last one and that was... yep, that was it, man."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"/>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA[On Remembering Dizzy Gillespie]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"/>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA["For the longest time, I used to call my wife -- I used to call Linda, my honey, and tell her, 'Honey, I called you and you weren't home.' You know?  She says, 'Honey, I've been home all day.' I said, 'Well, but I called' -- and then I'd say the number.  And she'd say, 'Honey, that's Dizzy's number.' "]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="23"/>
        <paragraph num="24"><![CDATA[   [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="131967779">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/2010/12/11/131967779/apple-co-founder-steve-wozniak-plays-not-my-job?ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=131967779&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/egdAIU</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Apple Co-Founder Steve Wozniak Plays Not My Job]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=131967779&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="131968208" type="primary">
        <title/>
        <duration>637</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1131968208-5c5c11.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1052&amp;aggIds=5163715&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=131968208&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1052&amp;aggIds=5163715&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=131968208&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1052&amp;aggIds=5163715&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
