      <audio id="130408743" type="standard">
        <title>Vargas Llosa, on politics and literature.</title>
        <duration>60</duration>
        <description>null</description>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1130408743-3409a8.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1033&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?staticUrl=/npr/blog/2010/10/20101007_blog_llosa1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1033&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?staticUrl=/npr/blog/2010/10/20101007_blog_llosa1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1033&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="false"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <audio id="130408911" type="standard">
        <title>Vargas Llosa, says "each book ... has been an adventure."</title>
        <duration>68</duration>
        <description>null</description>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1130408911-ff9edf.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1033&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?staticUrl=/npr/blog/2010/10/20101007_blog_vargas2&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1033&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?staticUrl=/npr/blog/2010/10/20101007_blog_vargas2&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1033&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="false"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="false"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[As we reported earlier, the Swedish Academy has awarded this year's Nobel Prize in Literature to Peruvian writer Mario Vargas Llosa, currently a visiting lecturer in creative writing in the Lewis Center for the Arts at Princeton University, in recognition of "his cartography of structures of power and his trenchant images of the individual's resistance, revolt, and defeat."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[This afternoon, NPR spoke to the newly-named laureate. Earlier today, he received a phone call from Peter Englund, permanent secretary of the Nobel Committee for Literature.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA["It was a big, big surprise," Vargas Llosa told NPR's Mary Louise Kelly. "For a moment, I thought this could be a joke."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[Almost an hour later, Englund told the world -- in three languages:]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"/>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA["I thought that, when I came to New York, that I would have a very life here, for three months, or three and a half months," Vargas Llosa said. "And my impression is that it won't be so quiet as I wanted."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Kelly asked him if he planned to use the prize as a platform to make political statements. (In 1990, Vargas Llosa ran for Peru's presidency.)]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"/>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[Let me say first that, although it is true that I have been participated in the political debate since i was young, I think it is very dangerous to use literature as a vehicle to promote political ideals. I think it is very risky because literature can become propaganda, and literature and propaganda are totally incompatible. I think literature can use politics, but that politics shouldn't use literature, because if it does, it destroys literature.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[So, when I want to make a political statement, I write an essay, I write an article, or I give a lecture.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[I think that literature is something that embraces a much larger experience than politics. It's an expression of what is life, of what are all the dimensions of life. But politics is one among others.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"/>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[Among the dozens he has authored, does Vargas Llosa have a favorite book?]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"/>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[Each book, for me, has been an adventure, a period of time dedicated to study, to document certain facts, to traveling and also to fantasize and to invent.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"/>
        <paragraph num="17"/>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[In general, a writer would like to think that the best book that he has written is the book that he is writing, and the next book will be even better. Maybe if this is not true, it is very useful to keep the illusion alive.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="130384028">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=130384028&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=130384028&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/8ZkVFY</link>
      <title><![CDATA[Few Traces Of Past Glory In Mogadishu]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=130384028&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="130395060" type="primary">
        <title>Listen to the Story</title>
        <duration>311</duration>
        <description/>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1130395060-3e6697.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1126&amp;aggIds=130385071&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?id=130395060&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1126&amp;aggIds=130385071&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?id=130395060&amp;type=1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1126&amp;aggIds=130385071&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
        </format>
        <rightsHolder/>
        <permissions>
          <download allow="true"/>
          <stream allow="true"/>
          <embed allow="true"/>
        </permissions>
      </audio>
      <text>
        <paragraph num="1"><![CDATA[Final of four parts]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="2"><![CDATA[The morning flight from Nairobi banks over the Indian Ocean and descends toward a runaway next to the beach. Waves crash and wind whips through sand dunes dotted with pockmarked buildings.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="3"><![CDATA[An abandoned jet lies near the edge of the runway with a broken wing.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="4"><![CDATA[The pilot comes on the intercom: "Welcome to Mogadishu, ladies and gentleman," he says. "The time now is 9:25."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="5"><![CDATA[So begins a four-day trip to one of the world’s most dangerous cities.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="6"><![CDATA[Mogadishu is the capital of Somalia, a country on the Horn of Africa that’s been embroiled in civil war for nearly two decades. Radical Islamists named al-Shabab are locked in a grinding battle with African peacekeeping troops.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="7"><![CDATA[Trapped in the middle are Somali civilians, just trying to stay alive amid the violence.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="8"><![CDATA[I'm traveling with a group of journalists -- guests of the African Union. The African Union has more than 7,000 troops here, defending a weak U.S.-backed government.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="9"><![CDATA[The soldiers say they’re pushing al-Shabab back and want to show off new forward bases. Before we head into town, our host, Ugandan Army Maj. Barigye Ba-Hoku, has this advice for our mostly white group: "Generally speaking, people of your complexion are targets for these idiots here. So, when we sit in our convoys, try as much as you can not to overexpose yourself. All right?"]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="10"><![CDATA[Wearing flak jackets and helmets, we board hulking, armored personnel carriers -- paid for by the U.S. government. The vehicles pull up to the edge of the heavily guarded African Union military base and launch into what feels like a road rally through the streets of Mogadishu.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="11"><![CDATA[The armored personnel carriers blow past palm trees and weave through Jersey barriers, kicking up trash in their wake.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="12"><![CDATA[There's not much shooting today, so people are selling fruit by the roadside beneath brightly colored umbrellas. A militia man allied with the government lounges in a plastic chair, a bandolier of bullets draped over his shoulders.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="13"><![CDATA[The vehicle is going at least 50 miles an hour. The reason is simple: The African Union does not want to offer al-Shabab a stationary target.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="14"><![CDATA[When the driver slows for a donkey in the road, he blasts his horn and then races ahead.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="15"><![CDATA[The high-speed tour of Mogadishu does not include famous landmarks that inspire national pride. Instead, it's filled with what used to be -- and places where terrible things happened.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="16"><![CDATA[Ba-Hoku points out the old U.S. Embassy, but you'd never recognize it. It's a collection of crumbling, sun-bleached buildings overgrown with brush.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="17"><![CDATA[He notes the Sahafi Hotel, not because of the service, but because two French security advisers were kidnapped there last year.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="18"><![CDATA[Eventually, we make our way back to the airport's concrete gate.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="19"><![CDATA[It's cracked and bears burn marks from a suicide bomb attack last month. African Union troops stopped the bombers, but not before they killed nine people, including two soldiers.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="20"><![CDATA[The African Union has set up hospitals to care for Somali civilians -- a popular service in a city where most hospitals closed long ago. By 7:30 on a Saturday morning, scores have lined up for help at an African Union Clinic. People with metal detectors check each patient for guns or bombs.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="21"><![CDATA[Among the neediest are children who've been caught in the crossfire.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="22"><![CDATA[An 11-year-old boy named Abdu was shot coming out of a mosque. He lies on a bed, his blue T-shirt pulled up over his chest. There is a gaping incision in his abdomen, which doctors opened to remove a sniper’s bullet.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="23"><![CDATA[Abdu's father, who waves a reed fan to shoo flies off his son, says the sniper was with al-Shabab. The boy moans in pain, unable to speak.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="24"><![CDATA[On the other side of the room is Howa Mudi, a 10-year-old girl with a brilliant smile. About three weeks ago, a mortar landed on her house, killing two of her siblings.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="25"><![CDATA[Howa was injured so badly, doctors had to amputate most of her legs.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="26"><![CDATA[Her father says he doesn't know who was responsible.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="27"><![CDATA[To record Howa in the noisy hospital ward, I use a special microphone that vaguely resembles a gun. She stares at it in horror and begins to shake.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="28"><![CDATA[Only when a doctor takes hold of the mic does Howa relax.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="29"><![CDATA["I'm unlucky," she says. "When I grow up, I don’t know what I'll do, because I don't have any legs."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="30"><![CDATA[Howa lost an older sister named Faduma in the attack. "Sometimes, when I sleep at night, I have dreams. I play with my sister," she says. "Then I wake up. This is my biggest problem."]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="31"><![CDATA[Mogadishu was not always like this. In the 1960s and 1970s, it was a haven for tourists who came for the beaches and blue-green waters that resemble the Mediterranean.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="32"><![CDATA[People called it the Pearl of the Indian  Ocean.]]></paragraph>
        <paragraph num="33"><![CDATA[Occasionally, amid the rubble, you can still catch glimpses of the city that once was -- a city that people in Mogadishu hope one day they'll see again.  [Copyright 2011 National Public Radio]]]></paragraph>
      </text>
    </story>
    <story id="130246283">
      <link type="html">http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=130246283&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</link>
      <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/query?id=130246283&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      <link type="short">http://n.pr/cFddYW</link>
      <title><![CDATA['Great Gatsby' Onstage, With A White-Collar Twist]]></title>
      <transcript>
        <link type="api">http://api.npr.org/transcript?id=130246283&amp;apiKey=MDA3MjY5MjE5MDEzMDE5MjY1NTczMzYzMA001</link>
      </transcript>
      <audio id="130245624" type="standard">
        <title>'In My Younger And More Vulnerable Years'</title>
        <duration>0</duration>
        <description>null</description>
        <format>
          <mp3 type="m3u">http://api.npr.org/m3u/1130245624-19a870.m3u?orgId=1&amp;topicId=1144&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</mp3>
          <wm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_wmref_em.php?staticUrl=/npr/me/2010/10/20101001_me_gatz1&amp;mtype=WM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1144&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</wm>
          <rm>http://www.npr.org/templates/dmg/dmg_rpm.rpm?staticUrl=/npr/me/2010/10/20101001_me_gatz1&amp;mtype=RM&amp;orgId=1&amp;topicId=1144&amp;ft=3&amp;f=</rm>
